fitk.graphics

Submodule for plotting of Fisher objects. See here for documentation of FisherFigure1D, FisherFigure2D, and FisherBarFigure.

   1"""
   2Submodule for plotting of Fisher objects.
   3See here for documentation of `FisherFigure1D`, `FisherFigure2D`, and `FisherBarFigure`.
   4"""

  44def _set_limits_2d(*, ax, size: int):
  45    for i, j in product(range(size), repeat=2):
  46        if i == j:
  47            ax[i, i].set_yticks([])
  48            ax[i, i].set_yticklabels([])
  49            if i < size - 1:
  50                ax[i, i].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
  51        if i > 0 and 0 < j < size - 1:
  52            ax[i, j].set_yticks([])
  53            ax[i, j].set_yticklabels([])
  54        if i > j and i != size - 1:
  55            ax[i, j].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
  56
  57
  58def _rescale_limits_2d(
  59    *,
  60    ax,
  61    size: int,
  62):
  63    for i, j in product(range(size), repeat=2):
  64        try:
  65            ax[i, j].relim()
  66            ax[i, j].autoscale_view()
  67            if i == j:
  68                ax[i, i].autoscale()
  69                ax[i, i].set_ylim(0, ax[i, i].get_ylim()[-1])
  70                ax[i, i].set_yticks([])
  71                ax[i, i].set_yticklabels([])
  72        except AttributeError:
  73            pass
  74
  75
  76def _mark_fiducials(
  77    *,
  78    fisher: FisherMatrix,
  79    ax,
  80    size: int,
  81    mark_fiducials: Union[bool, dict] = False,
  82):
  83    for i, j in product(range(size), repeat=2):
  84        try:
  85            if i == j:
  86                # marking the fiducials (1D)
  87                if mark_fiducials is not False:
  88                    if mark_fiducials is True:
  89                        mark_fiducials_1d = dict(linestyle="--", color="black")
  90                    else:
  91                        mark_fiducials_1d = mark_fiducials
  92
  93                    _mark_fiducial_1d(
  94                        fisher,
  95                        fisher.names[i],
  96                        ax[i, i],
  97                        **mark_fiducials_1d,
  98                    )
  99
 100            else:
 101                # marking the fiducials (2D)
 102                if mark_fiducials is not False:
 103                    if mark_fiducials is True:
 104                        mark_fiducials_2d = dict(linestyle="--", color="black")
 105                    else:
 106                        mark_fiducials_2d = mark_fiducials
 107
 108                    _mark_fiducial_2d(
 109                        fisher,
 110                        fisher.names[i],
 111                        fisher.names[j],
 112                        ax[i, j],
 113                        **mark_fiducials_2d,
 114                    )
 115
 116        except AttributeError:
 117            pass

 131class _FisherBaseFigure:
 132    def __init__(
 133        self,
 134        options: Optional[dict] = None,
 135        **kwargs,
 136    ):
 137        """
 138        Constructor
 139        """
 140        self._figure = None
 141        self._axes: Optional[Union[Axes, Sequence[Axes]]] = None
 142        self._handles: MutableSequence[Artist] = []
 143        self._labels: MutableSequence[str] = []
 144        self._options: dict = get_default_rcparams()
 145
 146        self.cycler = mpl.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"].by_key()["color"]
 147        self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
 148
 149        if options and "style" in options:
 150            style = options.pop("style")
 151            # maybe it's one of the built-in styles
 152            if style in mpl.style.available:
 153                self._options = {
 154                    **mpl.style.library[style],
 155                    **get_default_rcparams(),
 156                    **options,
 157                }
 158                # we need to reset the color cycler
 159                self.cycler = (
 160                    mpl.style.library[style]
 161                    .get(
 162                        "axes.prop_cycle",
 163                        mpl.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"],
 164                    )
 165                    .by_key()["color"]
 166                )
 167                self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
 168
 169            # maybe it's a file
 170            else:
 171                # we need to reset the color cycler
 172                self.cycler = (
 173                    mpl.rc_params_from_file(style)
 174                    .get(
 175                        "axes.prop_cycle",
 176                        mpl.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"],
 177                    )
 178                    .by_key()["color"]
 179                )
 180                self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
 181
 182                self._options = {
 183                    **mpl.rc_params_from_file(style),
 184                    **options,
 185                }
 186
 187    @property
 188    def options(self):
 189        """
 190        Returns the matplotlib options which were used for plotting.
 191        """
 192        return self._options
 193
 194    @property
 195    def axes(self):
 196        """
 197        Returns the axes of the figure as a numpy array.
 198        """
 199        return self._axes
 200
 201    @property
 202    def figure(self):
 203        """
 204        Returns the underlying figure, an instance of <a
 205        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/figure_api.html#matplotlib.figure.Figure"
 206        target="_blank" rel="noreferrer
 207        noopener">`matplotlib.figure.Figure`</a>.
 208        """
 209        return self._figure
 210
 211    @property
 212    def handles(self):
 213        """
 214        Returns the handles of the currently drawn artists.
 215        """
 216        return self._handles
 217
 218    @property
 219    def labels(self):
 220        """
 221        Returns the legend labels of the currently drawn artists.
 222        """
 223        return self._labels
 224
 225    def savefig(
 226        self,
 227        path: Union[str, Path],
 228        dpi: float = 300,
 229        bbox_inches: Union[str, Bbox] = "tight",
 230        **kwargs,
 231    ):
 232        """
 233        Convenience wrapper for <a
 234        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/figure_api.html#matplotlib.figure.Figure.savefig"
 235        target="_blank" rel="noreferrer
 236        noopener">`matplotlib.figure.Figure.savefig`</a>.
 237
 238        Parameters
 239        ----------
 240        path : Path or str
 241            the path where to save the figure
 242
 243        dpi : float, optional
 244            the resolution of the saved figure (default: 300)
 245
 246        bbox_inches : str or Bbox, optional
 247            what is the bounding box for the figure (default: 'tight')
 248
 249        **kwargs
 250            any other keyword arguments that should be passed to <a
 251            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/figure_api.html#matplotlib.figure.Figure.savefig"
 252            target="_blank" rel="noreferrer
 253            noopener">`matplotlib.figure.Figure.savefig`</a>
 254
 255        Returns
 256        -------
 257        None
 258
 259        Raises
 260        ------
 261        EmptyFigureError
 262            if `figure` is not set
 263        """
 264        if not self.figure:
 265            raise EmptyFigureError
 266
 267        self.figure.savefig(
 268            path,
 269            dpi=dpi,
 270            bbox_inches=bbox_inches,
 271            **kwargs,
 272        )
 273

 275class EmptyFigureError(Exception):
 276    """
 277    Error raised when the figure is empty
 278    """
 279
 280    def __init__(self):
 281        self.message = (
 282            "The figure is empty; make sure to call one of the plotting methods before"
 283        )
 284        super().__init__(self.message)

 287class _FisherMultipleAxesFigure(_FisherBaseFigure, ABC):
 288    """
 289    The abstract base class for plotting Fisher objects.
 290    """
 291
 292    def __init__(
 293        self,
 294        *args,
 295        options: Optional[dict] = None,
 296        hspace: float = 0.1,
 297        wspace: float = 0.1,
 298        contour_levels: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,
 299        **kwargs,
 300    ):
 301        """
 302        Constructor
 303        """
 304        self._names = None
 305        self._options: dict = {}
 306        self._ndim: int = 0
 307        self._hspace = hspace
 308        self._wspace = wspace
 309
 310        super().__init__(options=options, **kwargs)
 311
 312        # parse `contour_levels`
 313        if contour_levels is None:
 314            self.contour_levels = [(1.0, 0.3), (2.0, 0.1)]
 315        else:
 316            self.contour_levels = _parse_contour_levels(contour_levels)
 317
 318    @abstractmethod
 319    def plot(self, fisher: FisherMatrix, *args, **kwargs):
 320        """
 321        Implements plotting of Fisher objects.
 322        """
 323
 324    @abstractmethod
 325    def __getitem__(self, key):
 326        """
 327        Implements element access.
 328        """
 329
 330    @property
 331    def hspace(self) -> float:
 332        """
 333        The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed as
 334        a fraction of the average axis height.
 335        """
 336        return self._hspace
 337
 338    @property
 339    def wspace(self) -> float:
 340        """
 341        The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a
 342        fraction of the average axis width.
 343        """
 344        return self._wspace
 345
 346    @property
 347    def names(self):
 348        """
 349        Returns the names of the original parameters plotted.
 350        """
 351        return self._names
 352
 353    def __repr__(self):
 354        """
 355        Returns the representation of the figure
 356        """
 357        return (
 358            f"<{self.__class__.__name__}(\n"
 359            f"    names={repr(self.names)},\n"
 360            f"    figure={repr(self.figure)},\n"
 361            f"    axes={repr(self.axes)})>"
 362        )
 363
 364    def __str__(self):
 365        """
 366        Returns the string representation of the figure
 367        """
 368        return (
 369            f"{self.__class__.__name__}(\n"
 370            f"    names={str(self.names)},\n"
 371            f"    figure={str(self.figure)},\n"
 372            f"    axes={str(self.axes)})"
 373        )
 374
 375    def add_artist_to_legend(
 376        self,
 377        artist: Artist,
 378        label: str,
 379    ):
 380        r"""
 381        This is a convenience function for correctly updating the legend after
 382        directly plotting some artist via `<instance>[<name(s)>].<method>`
 383
 384        Parameters
 385        ----------
 386        artist
 387            the artist which we want to put on the legend
 388
 389        label : str
 390            the label for the artist
 391
 392        Returns
 393        -------
 394        None
 395
 396        Examples
 397        --------
 398        Setup the plot:
 399        >>> fig = FisherFigure1D()
 400        >>> fig.plot(FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2]), names=["a", "b"]), label="Fisher matrix")
 401
 402        Add something to the plot that has a handle:
 403        >>> handle, = fig["a"].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
 404
 405        Finally, add the handle to the legend, and draw the legend:
 406        >>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(handle, "linear function")
 407        >>> _ = fig.legend() # the artist will now be shown correctly in the legend
 408
 409        Save it to a file:
 410        >>> fig.savefig(
 411        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure2d_add_artist_to_legend1.png",
 412        ... dpi=150)
 413

 415
 416        Notes
 417        -----
 418        The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
 419        """
 420        self.labels.append(label)
 421        self.handles.append(artist)
 422
 423    def set_label_params(
 424        self,
 425        which: str = "both",
 426        **kwargs,
 427    ):
 428        """
 429        Collectively sets both x and y label parameters.
 430
 431        Parameters
 432        ----------
 433        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 434            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 435
 436        **kwargs
 437            any keyword arguments that are also valid for <a
 438            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/text_api.html#matplotlib.text.Text"
 439            target="_blank" rel="noopener
 440            noreferrer">`matplotlib.text.Text`</a>.
 441
 442        Returns
 443        -------
 444        None
 445
 446        Raises
 447        ------
 448        EmptyFigureError
 449            if `figure` is not set
 450        """
 451        if not self.figure:
 452            raise EmptyFigureError
 453
 454        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 455            # only set the parameters which are not empty (should this be done
 456            # for all of them instead?)
 457            if (
 458                self[nameiter]
 459                and self[nameiter].get_xlabel()
 460                and which in ["both", "x"]
 461            ):
 462                self[nameiter].set_xlabel(
 463                    self[nameiter].get_xlabel(),
 464                    **kwargs,
 465                )
 466            if (
 467                self[nameiter]
 468                and self[nameiter].get_ylabel()
 469                and which in ["both", "y"]
 470            ):
 471                self[nameiter].set_ylabel(
 472                    self[nameiter].get_ylabel(),
 473                    **kwargs,
 474                )
 475
 476    def set_tick_params(
 477        self,
 478        which: str = "both",
 479        **kwargs,
 480    ):
 481        """
 482        Collectively sets both x and y tick parameters.
 483
 484        Parameters
 485        ----------
 486        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 487            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 488
 489        **kwargs
 490            any keyword arguments passed to the methods for handling tick
 491            parameters (such as 'fontsize', 'rotation', etc.)
 492
 493        Returns
 494        -------
 495        None
 496
 497        Raises
 498        ------
 499        EmptyFigureError
 500            if `figure` is not set
 501
 502        ValueError
 503            if `which` is not one of the allowed values
 504        """
 505        if not self.figure:
 506            raise EmptyFigureError
 507
 508        allowed_axis: dict[str, list[str]] = {
 509            "both": ["x", "y"],
 510            "x": ["x"],
 511            "y": ["y"],
 512        }
 513
 514        if which not in allowed_axis:
 515            raise ValueError(
 516                f"Argument `which={which}` is not one of {list(allowed_axis.keys())}"
 517            )
 518
 519        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 520            if self[nameiter]:
 521                for axis in allowed_axis[which]:
 522                    for item in getattr(self[nameiter], f"get_{axis}ticklabels")():
 523                        for key, value in kwargs.items():
 524                            getattr(item, f"set_{key}")(value)
 525
 526            # also alter any exponential offsets
 527            for key, value in kwargs.items():
 528                if self[nameiter]:
 529                    for axis in allowed_axis[which]:
 530                        getattr(
 531                            getattr(
 532                                self[nameiter], f"get_{axis}axis"
 533                            )().get_offset_text(),
 534                            f"set_{key}",
 535                        )(value)
 536
 537    def set_major_locator(
 538        self,
 539        locator: Locator,
 540        which: str = "both",
 541    ):
 542        """
 543        Sets the major locator for all of the axes.
 544
 545        Parameters
 546        ----------
 547        locator
 548            the instance of <a
 549            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/ticker_api.html#matplotlib.ticker.Locator"
 550            target="_blank" rel="noopener
 551            noreferrer">`matplotlib.ticker.Locator`</a> to use.
 552
 553        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 554            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 555
 556        Returns
 557        -------
 558        None
 559
 560        Raises
 561        ------
 562        EmptyFigureError
 563            if `figure` is not set
 564        """
 565        if not self.figure:
 566            raise EmptyFigureError
 567
 568        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 569            # for some reason, we cannot reuse the same instance, so we just
 570            # make a deep copy of it instead
 571            if (
 572                self[nameiter]
 573                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_xticks())
 574                and which in ["both", "x"]
 575            ):
 576                xloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
 577                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_major_locator(xloc)
 578            if (
 579                self[nameiter]
 580                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_yticks())
 581                and which in ["both", "y"]
 582            ):
 583                yloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
 584                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_major_locator(yloc)
 585
 586    def set_minor_locator(
 587        self,
 588        locator: Locator,
 589        which: str = "both",
 590    ):
 591        """
 592        Sets the minor locator for all of the axes.
 593
 594        Parameters
 595        ----------
 596        locator
 597            the instance of <a
 598            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/ticker_api.html#matplotlib.ticker.Locator"
 599            target="_blank" rel="noopener
 600            noreferrer">`matplotlib.ticker.Locator`</a> to use.
 601
 602        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 603            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 604
 605        Returns
 606        -------
 607        None
 608
 609        Raises
 610        ------
 611        EmptyFigureError
 612            if `figure` is not set
 613        """
 614        if not self.figure:
 615            raise EmptyFigureError
 616
 617        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 618            if (
 619                self[nameiter]
 620                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_xticks())
 621                and which in ["both", "x"]
 622            ):
 623                # same reason as the major locator
 624                xloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
 625                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_minor_locator(xloc)
 626            if (
 627                self[nameiter]
 628                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_yticks())
 629                and which in ["both", "y"]
 630            ):
 631                yloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
 632                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_minor_locator(yloc)
 633
 634    def set_major_formatter(
 635        self,
 636        formatter: Formatter,
 637        which: str = "both",
 638    ):
 639        """
 640        Sets the major formatter for all of the axes.
 641
 642        Parameters
 643        ----------
 644        formatter
 645            the instance of <a
 646            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/ticker_api.html#matplotlib.ticker.Formatter"
 647            target="_blank" rel="noopener
 648            noreferrer">`matplotlib.ticker.Formatter`</a> to use.
 649
 650        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 651            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 652
 653        Returns
 654        -------
 655        None
 656
 657        Raises
 658        ------
 659        EmptyFigureError
 660            if `figure` is not set
 661        """
 662        if not self.figure:
 663            raise EmptyFigureError
 664
 665        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 666            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
 667                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
 668            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
 669                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
 670
 671    def set_minor_formatter(
 672        self,
 673        formatter: Formatter,
 674        which: str = "both",
 675    ):
 676        """
 677        Sets the minor formatter for all of the axes.
 678
 679        Parameters
 680        ----------
 681        formatter
 682            the instance of <a
 683            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/ticker_api.html#matplotlib.ticker.Formatter"
 684            target="_blank" rel="noopener
 685            noreferrer">`matplotlib.ticker.Formatter`</a> to use.
 686
 687        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 688            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 689
 690        Returns
 691        -------
 692        None
 693
 694        Raises
 695        ------
 696        EmptyFigureError
 697            if `figure` is not set
 698        """
 699        if not self.figure:
 700            raise EmptyFigureError
 701
 702        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 703            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
 704                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_minor_formatter(formatter)
 705            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
 706                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_minor_formatter(formatter)
 707
 708
 709class FisherBarFigure(_FisherBaseFigure):
 710    """
 711    Container for plotting single-axis bar-like figures
 712    (`plot_absolute_constraints` and `plot_relative_constraints`)
 713    """
 714
 715    def _parse_fractional_constraints(
 716        self,
 717        args: Sequence[FisherMatrix],
 718        marginalized: bool = True,
 719        colors: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 720        labels: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 721        values_label: Optional[str] = None,
 722        percent: bool = False,
 723        space: float = 0.3,
 724        scale: str = "linear",
 725    ):
 726        # error handling
 727        if not 0 <= space <= 1:
 728            raise ValueError("The value of `space` must be in the open interval (0, 1)")
 729
 730        allowed_scales = ["linear", "log", "symlog"]
 731        if scale not in allowed_scales:
 732            raise ValueError(f"The value of `scale` must be one of: {allowed_scales}")
 733
 734        for arg in args:
 735            if set(args[0].names) != set(arg.names):
 736                raise MismatchingValuesError(
 737                    "parameter name",
 738                    args[0].names,
 739                    arg.names,
 740                )
 741
 742        # reordering to match the first one
 743        args = [arg.sort(key=args[0].names) for arg in args]
 744
 745        # total number of parameters in the Fisher objects
 746        size = len(args[0])
 747
 748        # the width or height of all columns for a single parameter
 749        total_space = 1 - space
 750
 751        # the width or height of a single column for a single parameter
 752        space_per_object = total_space / len(args)
 753
 754        if not colors:
 755            colors = list(islice(self.current_color, len(args)))  # type: ignore
 756        elif len(colors) != len(args):
 757            raise MismatchingSizeError(colors, args)
 758
 759        if not labels:
 760            labels = [""] * len(args)
 761        elif len(labels) != len(args):
 762            raise MismatchingSizeError(labels, args)
 763
 764        if not values_label:
 765            if percent:
 766                values_label = r"$\sigma / \theta_\mathrm{fid}\ (\%)$"
 767            else:
 768                values_label = r"$\sigma / \theta_\mathrm{fid}$"
 769
 770        return _TempContainer(
 771            labels,
 772            colors,  # type: ignore
 773            [
 774                [
 775                    _ - total_space / 2 + (2 * index + 1) * space_per_object / 2
 776                    for _ in range(size)
 777                ]
 778                for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 779            ],
 780            [
 781                np.array(
 782                    [
 783                        arg.constraints(name=_, marginalized=marginalized)[0]
 784                        for _ in arg.names
 785                    ]
 786                )
 787                / np.array(
 788                    [
 789                        np.abs(fid) if not np.isclose(fid, 0) else 1
 790                        for fid in arg.fiducials
 791                    ]
 792                )
 793                for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 794            ],
 795            space_per_object=space_per_object,
 796            values_label=values_label,
 797            scale=scale,
 798        )
 799
 800    def plot_absolute_constraints(
 801        self,
 802        args: Sequence[FisherMatrix],
 803        kind: str,
 804        marginalized: bool = True,
 805        colors: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 806        labels: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 807        values_label: Optional[str] = None,
 808        scale: str = "linear",
 809        space: float = 0.3,
 810        capsize: Optional[float] = None,
 811        **kwargs,
 812    ):
 813        r"""
 814        Makes a plot of the constraints of the Fisher matrices
 815
 816        Parameters
 817        ----------
 818        args : array_like of FisherMatrix
 819            the Fisher matrices for which we want to plot the constraints
 820
 821        kind : str, {'bar', 'barh', 'errorbar'}
 822            the kind of plot we want (vertical bar, horizontal bar, errorbar)
 823
 824        marginalized : bool, optional
 825            whether the marginalized or the unmarginalized constraints should
 826            be plotted (default: True)
 827
 828        colors : array_like of str, optional
 829            the colors to use for the plotting (default: default matplotlib
 830            colors)
 831
 832        labels : array_like of str, optional
 833            the labels for the Fisher matrices (default: None)
 834
 835        values_label : str, optional
 836            the label for the axis containing the constraints (default:
 837            `$\theta_\mathrm{fid}$`)
 838
 839        scale : str, {'linear', 'log'}
 840            the scale used for the y axis (default: 'linear')
 841
 842        space : float, optional
 843            the space reserved between the bars (default: 0.3)
 844
 845        capsize : float, optional
 846            the width of the errorbars (default: none, that is, determined
 847            automatically)
 848
 849        **kwargs
 850            any keyword arguments passed to <a
 851            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.bar.html"
 852            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer
 853            noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.bar`</a>, or <a
 854            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.barh.html"
 855            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer
 856            noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.barh`</a>, or <a
 857            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.errorbar.html"
 858            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer
 859            noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.errorbar`</a>.
 860        Returns
 861        -------
 862        None
 863
 864        Examples
 865        --------
 866        Define some Fisher matrices:
 867        >>> fm1 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2, 3]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.3, 0.7, 0.96])
 868        >>> fm2 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([4, 5, 6]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.35, 0.67, 0.9])
 869
 870        Make a vertical bar plot:
 871        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
 872        >>> fig.plot_absolute_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'bar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
 873        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()
 874
 875        Save it to a file:
 876        >>> fig.savefig(
 877        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_absolute_constraints_bar.png",
 878        ... dpi=150)
 879
 880        <img width="100%"  894        Make an errobar plot:
 895        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
 896        >>> fig.plot_absolute_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'errorbar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'], capsize=4)
 897        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()
 898
 899        Save it to a file:
 900        >>> fig.savefig(
 901        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_absolute_constraints_errorbar.png",
 902        ... dpi=150)

 905        """
 906        size = len(args[0])
 907        latex_names = args[0].latex_names
 908
 909        # error handling
 910        if not 0 <= space <= 1:
 911            raise ValueError("The value of `space` must be in the open interval (0, 1)")
 912
 913        allowed_scales = ["linear", "log"]
 914        if scale not in allowed_scales:
 915            raise ValueError(f"The value of `scale` must be one of: {allowed_scales}")
 916
 917        for arg in args:
 918            if set(args[0].names) != set(arg.names):
 919                raise MismatchingValuesError(
 920                    "parameter name",
 921                    args[0].names,
 922                    arg.names,
 923                )
 924
 925        # reordering to match the first one
 926        args = [arg.sort(key=args[0].names) for arg in args]
 927
 928        # the width or height of all columns for a single parameter
 929        total_space = 1 - space
 930
 931        # the width or height of a single column for a single parameter
 932        space_per_object = total_space / len(args)
 933
 934        if not colors:
 935            colors = list(islice(self.current_color, len(args)))  # type: ignore
 936        elif len(colors) != len(args):
 937            raise MismatchingSizeError(colors, args)
 938
 939        if not labels:
 940            labels = [""] * len(args)
 941        elif len(labels) != len(args):
 942            raise MismatchingSizeError(labels, args)
 943
 944        if not values_label:
 945            values_label = r"$\theta_\mathrm{fid}$"
 946
 947        x_array = [
 948            [
 949                _ - total_space / 2 + (2 * index + 1) * space_per_object / 2
 950                for _ in range(size)
 951            ]
 952            for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 953        ]
 954        y_array = [arg.fiducials for arg in args]
 955        yerr_array = [
 956            np.array(
 957                [
 958                    arg.constraints(name=_, marginalized=marginalized)[0]
 959                    for _ in arg.names
 960                ]
 961            )
 962            for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 963        ]
 964
 965        # TODO: maybe put this in a class so validation is easier
 966        options = {
 967            "bar": {
 968                "parameters_scale": "x",
 969                "values_scale": "y",
 970                "error_name": "yerr",
 971                "extra_kwargs": {
 972                    "capsize": total_space * 60 / len(args) / size,
 973                    "width": space_per_object,
 974                },
 975            },
 976            "barh": {
 977                "parameters_scale": "y",
 978                "values_scale": "x",
 979                "error_name": "xerr",
 980                "extra_kwargs": {
 981                    "capsize": total_space * 60 / len(args) / size,
 982                    "height": space_per_object,
 983                },
 984            },
 985            "errorbar": {
 986                "parameters_scale": "x",
 987                "values_scale": "y",
 988                "error_name": "yerr",
 989                "extra_kwargs": {
 990                    "capsize": total_space * 120 / len(args) / size,
 991                    "ls": kwargs.pop("ls", ""),
 992                    "marker": kwargs.pop("marker", "o"),
 993                },
 994            },
 995        }
 996
 997        if capsize is not None:
 998            options[kind]["extra_kwargs"]["capsize"] = capsize  # type: ignore
 999
1000        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1001            fig, ax = plt.subplots()
1002            for color, label, x, y, yerr in zip(
1003                colors,  # type: ignore
1004                labels,
1005                x_array,
1006                y_array,
1007                yerr_array,
1008            ):
1009                getattr(ax, kind)(
1010                    x,
1011                    y,
1012                    color=color,
1013                    label=label,
1014                    **{options[kind]["error_name"]: yerr},
1015                    **options[kind]["extra_kwargs"],
1016                    **kwargs,
1017                )
1018
1019            ax.set_yscale(scale)
1020
1021            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticks')(range(size))
1022            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticklabels')(
1023                latex_names
1024            )
1025            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["values_scale"]}label')(values_label)
1026
1027        self._figure = fig
1028        self._axes = ax
1029
1030    def plot_relative_constraints(
1031        self,
1032        args: Sequence[FisherMatrix],
1033        kind: str,
1034        marginalized: bool = True,
1035        colors: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
1036        labels: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
1037        values_label: Optional[str] = None,
1038        scale: str = "linear",
1039        space: float = 0.3,
1040        percent: bool = False,
1041        **kwargs,
1042    ):
1043        r"""
1044        Makes a plot of the constraints (relative to the fiducial) of the
1045        Fisher matrices
1046
1047        Parameters
1048        ----------
1049        args : array_like of FisherMatrix
1050            the Fisher matrices for which we want to plot the constraints
1051
1052        kind : str, {'bar', 'barh', 'errorbar'}
1053            the kind of plot we want (vertical bar, horizontal bar, errorbar)
1054
1055        marginalized : bool, optional
1056            whether the marginalized or the unmarginalized constraints should
1057            be plotted (default: True)
1058
1059        colors : array_like of str, optional
1060            the colors to use for the plotting (default: default matplotlib
1061            colors)
1062
1063        labels : array_like of str, optional
1064            the labels for the Fisher matrices (default: None)
1065
1066        values_label : str, optional
1067            the label for the values, that is, the y axis (default: `$\sigma /
1068            \theta_\mathrm{fid}$` if `percent` is false, otherwise `$\sigma /
1069            \theta_\mathrm{fid}\ (\%)$`
1070
1071        scale : str, {'linear', 'log'}
1072            the scale used for the y axis (default: 'linear')
1073
1074        space : float, optional
1075            the space reserved between the bars (default: 0.3)
1076
1077        percent : bool, optional
1078            whether to plot in percentage units (default: false)
1079
1080        **kwargs
1081            any keyword arguments passed to
1082            <a
1083            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.bar.html"
1084            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.bar`</a>
1085
1086        Returns
1087        -------
1088        None
1089
1090        Examples
1091        --------
1092        Define some Fisher matrices:
1093        >>> fm1 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2, 3]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.3, 0.7, 0.96])
1094        >>> fm2 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([4, 5, 6]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.35, 0.67, 0.9])
1095
1096        Make a vertical bar plot:
1097        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
1098        >>> fig.plot_relative_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'bar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
1099        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()
1100
1101        Save it to a file:
1102        >>> fig.savefig(
1103        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_relative_constraints_bar.png",
1104        ... dpi=150)
1105

1108        Make a horizontal bar plot:
1109        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
1110        >>> fig.plot_relative_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'barh', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])

1114        >>> fig.savefig(

1119        """
1120        size = len(args[0])
1121        latex_names = args[0].latex_names
1122
1123        computed_parameters = self._parse_fractional_constraints(
1124            args,
1125            marginalized=marginalized,
1126            colors=colors,
1127            labels=labels,
1128            scale=scale,
1129            space=space,
1130            values_label=values_label,
1131            percent=percent,
1132        )
1133
1134        # TODO: maybe put this in a class so validation is easier
1135        options = {
1136            "bar": {
1137                "parameters_scale": "x",
1138                "values_scale": "y",
1139                "lines_prefix": "h",
1140                "extra_kwargs": {
1141                    "width": computed_parameters.space_per_object,
1142                },
1143            },
1144            "barh": {
1145                "parameters_scale": "y",
1146                "values_scale": "x",
1147                "lines_prefix": "v",
1148                "extra_kwargs": {
1149                    "height": computed_parameters.space_per_object,
1150                },
1151            },
1152        }
1153
1154        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1155            fig, ax = plt.subplots()
1156            for color, label, x, y in zip(
1157                computed_parameters.colors,
1158                computed_parameters.labels,
1159                computed_parameters.x_array,
1160                computed_parameters.y_array,
1161            ):
1162                getattr(ax, kind)(
1163                    x,
1164                    y * 100 if percent else y,
1165                    color=color,
1166                    label=label,
1167                    **options[kind]["extra_kwargs"],
1168                    **kwargs,
1169                )
1170                getattr(ax, kind)(
1171                    x,
1172                    -(y * 100 if percent else y),
1173                    color=color,
1174                    label=None,
1175                    **options[kind]["extra_kwargs"],
1176                    **kwargs,
1177                )
1178
1179            limits = getattr(ax, f'get_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}lim')()
1180
1181            getattr(ax, f'{options[kind]["lines_prefix"]}lines')(
1182                0, limits[0], limits[-1], color="black", ls="--"
1183            )
1184            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}lim')(*limits)
1185            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["values_scale"]}scale')(
1186                computed_parameters.scale
1187            )
1188
1189            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticks')(range(size))
1190            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticklabels')(
1191                latex_names
1192            )
1193            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["values_scale"]}label')(
1194                computed_parameters.values_label
1195            )
1196
1197        self._figure = fig
1198        self._axes = ax
1199

1201class FisherFigure1D(_FisherMultipleAxesFigure):
1202    r"""
1203    Container for easy access to elements in the 1D plot.
1204
1205    Examples
1206    --------
1207    Define some Fisher matrices:
1208    >>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
1209    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
1210    ... names=['a', 'b'],
1211    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
1212    ... )
1213    >>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
1214    ... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
1215    ... names=['a', 'b'],
1216    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
1217    ... )
1218
1219    Instantiate a figure:
1220    >>> fig = FisherFigure1D()
1221
1222    Draw marginalized 1D plots with the previously defined Fisher matrix:
1223    >>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')
1224
1225    Add another plot with a different color and style:
1226    >>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')
1227
1228    Draw some other stuff on it:
1229    >>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red', label='curve')
1230    >>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
1231    >>> # artist, = fig['a'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
1232    >>> # note that in this case, due to certain limitations, you need to
1233    >>> # manually add the legend using a convenience function:
1234    >>> # fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')
1235
1236    Add a legend:
1237    >>> _ = fig.legend(ncol=3, loc='center')
1238
1239    Add a title:
1240    >>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 1D plotting')
1241
1242    Save it to a file:
1243    >>> fig.savefig(
1244    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure1d_example1.png",
1245    ... dpi=150)
1246

1249
1250    def __init__(
1251        self,
1252        options: Optional[dict] = None,
1253        max_cols: Optional[int] = None,
1254        hspace: float = 0.5,
1255        wspace: float = 0.1,
1256        contour_levels: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,
1257    ):
1258        """
1259        Constructor.
1260
1261        Parameters
1262        ----------
1263        options : dict, optional
1264            the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special
1265            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can
1266            be one of the outputs of <a
1267            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/style_api.html#matplotlib.style.matplotlib.style.available"
1268            target="_blank" rel="noopener
1269            noreferrer">`matplotlib.style.available`</a>, or a path to a file.
1270            If using a file, does not use the default rc parameters).
1271
1272        max_cols : int, optional
1273            the maximum number of columns in the final plot
1274
1275        hspace : float, optional
1276            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1277            as a fraction of the average axis height.
1278
1279        wspace : float, optional
1280            The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1281            as a fraction of the average axis width.
1282
1283        contour_levels : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1284            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded, along with
1285            the associated opacity (default: None). If not specified, defaults
1286            to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1287
1288        Notes
1289        -----
1290        For the style sheet reference, please consult <a
1291        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html"
1292        target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">the matplotlib
1293        documentation</a>.
1294        """
1295        super().__init__(
1296            options=options,
1297            wspace=wspace,
1298            hspace=hspace,
1299            contour_levels=contour_levels,
1300        )
1301        self.max_cols = max_cols
1302        self._ndim = 1
1303        self._hspace = hspace
1304        self._wspace = wspace
1305
1306    def __getitem__(
1307        self,
1308        key: str,
1309    ):
1310        """
1311        Returns the axis associated to the name `key`.
1312        """
1313        if not self.figure:
1314            raise EmptyFigureError
1315
1316        if key not in self.names:
1317            raise ParameterNotFoundError(key, self.names)
1318
1319        return self.axes.flat[np.where(self.names == key)][0]
1320
1321    def draw(
1322        self,
1323        name: str,
1324        method: str,
1325        *args,
1326        **kwargs,
1327    ):
1328        """
1329        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis where the parameter
1330        `name` has already been plotted.
1331
1332        Parameters
1333        ----------
1334        name : str
1335            the name (label) of the parameter where we want to draw
1336
1337        method : str
1338            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as <a
1339            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.plot.html"
1340            target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">`plot`</a>, <a
1341            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.scatter.html"
1342            target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">`scatter`</a>, etc.)
1343
1344        *args
1345            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
1346
1347        **kwargs
1348            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
1349
1350        Returns
1351        -------
1352        Artist
1353            the artist that was drawn on the axis
1354
1355        Raises
1356        ------
1357        EmptyFigureError
1358            if `figure` is not set
1359
1360        AttributeError
1361            if `method` is not a valid plotting method
1362        """
1363        if not hasattr(self[name], method):
1364            raise AttributeError(
1365                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
1366            )
1367
1368        # get the right color
1369        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1370            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1371            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1372
1373        # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection of
1374        # artists
1375        handles = getattr(self[name], method)(*args, **kwargs)
1376        if is_iterable(handles):
1377            for handle in handles:
1378                if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1379                    self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
1380                    self.handles.append(handle)
1381        else:
1382            if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1383                self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
1384                self.handles.append(handles)
1385
1386        self[name].autoscale()
1387        self[name].relim()
1388        self[name].autoscale_view()
1389
1390        return handles
1391
1392    def plot(
1393        self,
1394        fisher: FisherMatrix,
1395        *args,
1396        mark_fiducials: Union[bool, dict] = False,
1397        **kwargs,
1398    ):
1399        """
1400        Plots the 1D curves of the Fisher objects.
1401
1402        Parameters
1403        ----------
1404        fisher
1405            the Fisher object which we want to plot
1406
1407        mark_fiducials : bool or dict, optional
1408            whether or not the fiducials should be marked on the plots
1409            (default: False). If set to `True`, uses `linestyle='--'` and
1410            `color='black'` as the default. If a dictionary, accepts the same
1411            keyword arguments as <a
1412            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline.html#matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline"
1413            target="_blank" rel="noreferrer
1414            noopener">`matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline`</a>.  If an empty
1415            dictionary, uses the default style (determined automatically).
1416
1417        **kwargs
1418            any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as `plot_curve_1d`)
1419
1420        Returns
1421        -------
1422        None
1423        """
1424        size = len(fisher)
1425
1426        added = False
1427
1428        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
1429        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
1430        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1431            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1432            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1433
1434        if self.max_cols is not None and self.max_cols <= size:
1435            full = size % self.max_cols == 0
1436            layout = (
1437                size // self.max_cols if full else size // self.max_cols + 1,
1438                self.max_cols,
1439            )
1440        else:
1441            layout = 1, size
1442            full = True
1443
1444        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1445            # general figure setup
1446            if self.figure:
1447                fig = self.figure
1448                axes = self.axes
1449            else:
1450                fig = plt.figure(
1451                    clear=True,
1452                    figsize=(2 * layout[1], 2 * layout[0]),
1453                )
1454                gs = fig.add_gridspec(
1455                    nrows=layout[0],
1456                    ncols=layout[1],
1457                    hspace=self.hspace,
1458                    wspace=self.wspace,
1459                )
1460                axes = gs.subplots()
1461                if size == 1:
1462                    axes = np.array([axes])
1463
1464            for (index, name), latex_name in zip(
1465                enumerate(fisher.names),
1466                fisher.latex_names,
1467            ):
1468                ax = axes.flat[index]
1469
1470                _, __, handle = plot_curve_1d(fisher, name, ax, **kwargs)
1471
1472                if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
1473                    self.handles.append(handle)
1474                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1475                    added = True
1476
1477                for contour_level in self.contour_levels:
1478                    _add_shading_1d(
1479                        fisher.fiducials[index],
1480                        fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True),
1481                        ax,
1482                        level=contour_level[0],
1483                        alpha=contour_level[1],
1484                        **kwargs,
1485                    )
1486
1487                ax.autoscale()
1488                ax.set_xlabel(latex_name)
1489                ax.relim()
1490                ax.autoscale_view()
1491
1492                # the y axis should start at 0 since we're plotting a PDF
1493                ax.set_ylim(0, ax.get_ylim()[-1])
1494
1495                ax.set_yticks([])
1496
1497                # marking the fiducials
1498                if not mark_fiducials is False:
1499                    if mark_fiducials is True:
1500                        mark_fiducials = dict(linestyle="--", color="black")
1501
1502                    _mark_fiducial_1d(
1503                        fisher,
1504                        fisher.names[index],
1505                        ax,
1506                        **mark_fiducials,
1507                    )
1508
1509            # remove any axes which are not drawn
1510            if not full:
1511                for index in range(
1512                    size,
1513                    layout[0] * layout[1],
1514                ):
1515                    # it's simpler to turn off the axis, than completely remove
1516                    # it
1517                    axes.flat[index].axis("off")
1518
1519        self._figure = fig
1520        self._axes = axes
1521        self._names = fisher.names
1522
1523    def legend(
1524        self,
1525        *args: Artist,
1526        overwrite: bool = False,
1527        loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = "lower center",
1528        bbox_to_anchor: Any = (0.5, 1),
1529        **kwargs,
1530    ):
1531        """
1532        Creates a legend on the figure.
1533
1534        Parameters
1535        ----------
1536        *args
1537            any positional arguments for the legend
1538
1539        overwrite : bool, optional
1540            whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by `fitk` (default:
1541            False)
1542
1543        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
1544            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
1545            (default: 'lower center')
1546
1547        bbox_to_anchor : Any, optional
1548            the location of where to place the legend (default: `[0.5, 1]`)
1549
1550        **kwargs
1551            any other keyword arguments for the legend
1552
1553        Returns
1554        -------
1555        Artist
1556            the legend that was drawn on the figure
1557
1558        Raises
1559        ------
1560        EmptyFigureError
1561            if `figure` is not set
1562        """
1563        if not self.figure:
1564            raise EmptyFigureError
1565
1566        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1567            ax = self.axes.flat[0]
1568            if not overwrite:
1569                if ax.get_legend():
1570                    ax.get_legend().remove()
1571
1572                return ax.legend(
1573                    self.handles,
1574                    self.labels,
1575                    loc=loc,
1576                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1577                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
1578                    **kwargs,
1579                )
1580
1581            return ax.legend(
1582                *args,
1583                loc=loc,
1584                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1585                **kwargs,
1586            )
1587
1588    def set_title(
1589        self,
1590        *args,
1591        x: float = 0.5,
1592        y: float = 1.2,
1593        **kwargs,
1594    ):
1595        """
1596        Thin wrapper for setting the title of the figure with the correct
1597        options.
1598
1599        Parameters
1600        ----------
1601        *args
1602            any positional arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1603
1604        x : float, optional
1605            the x position of the title (default: `0.5`)
1606
1607        y : float, optional
1608            the y position of the title (default: `1.2`)
1609
1610        **kwargs
1611            any keyword arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1612
1613        Returns
1614        -------
1615        Artist
1616            the title that was drawn on the figure
1617
1618        Raises
1619        ------
1620        EmptyFigureError
1621            if `figure` is not set
1622        """
1623        if not self.figure:
1624            raise EmptyFigureError
1625
1626        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1627            return self.figure.suptitle(*args, x=x, y=y, **kwargs)
1628
1629
1630class FisherFigure2D(_FisherMultipleAxesFigure):
1631    r"""
1632    Container for easy access to elements in the 2D plot.
1633
1634    Examples
1635    --------
1636    Define some Fisher matrices:
1637    >>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
1638    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
1639    ... names=['a', 'b'],
1640    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
1641    ... )
1642    >>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
1643    ... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
1644    ... names=['a', 'b'],
1645    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
1646    ... )
1647
1648    Instantiate a figure:
1649    >>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)
1650
1651    Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:
1652    >>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')
1653
1654    Add a plot with a different color and style:
1655    >>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')
1656
1657    Draw some other stuff on it:
1658    >>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'b', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red', label='curve')
1659    >>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
1660    >>> # artist, = fig['a', 'b'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
1661    >>> # note that in this case, due to certain limitations, you need to
1662    >>> # manually add the legend using a convenience function:
1663    >>> # fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')
1664
1665    Add a legend:
1666    >>> _ = fig.legend()
1667
1668    Add a title:
1669    >>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 2D plotting')
1670
1671    Save it to a file:
1672    >>> fig.savefig(
1673    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure2d_example1.png",
1674    ... dpi=150)
1675

1687        contour_levels_1d: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,
1688        contour_levels_2d: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,
1689    ):
1690        """
1691        Constructor.
1692
1693        Parameters
1694        ----------
1695        options : dict, optional
1696            the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special
1697            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can
1698            be one of the outputs of <a
1699            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/style_api.html#matplotlib.style.matplotlib.style.available"
1700            target="_blank" rel="noopener
1701            noreferrer">`matplotlib.style.available`</a>, or a path to a file.
1702            If using a file, does not use the default rc parameters).
1703
1704        hspace : float, optional
1705            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1706            as a fraction of the average axis height.
1707
1708        wspace : float, optional
1709            The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1710            as a fraction of the average axis width.
1711
1712        show_1d_curves : bool, optional
1713            whether the 1D marginalized curves should be plotted (default:
1714            False)
1715
1716        show_joint_dist : bool, optional
1717            whether to plot the isocontours of the joint distribution (default:
1718            False)
1719
1720        contour_levels : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1721            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded, along with
1722            the associated opacity (default: None). If not specified, defaults
1723            to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1724
1725        contour_levels_1d : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1726            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded (on the 1D
1727            plots), along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not
1728            specified, defaults to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1729
1730        contour_levels_2d : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1731            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded (on the 2D
1732            plots), along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not
1733            specified, defaults to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1734
1735        Notes
1736        -----
1737        For the style sheet reference, please consult <a
1738        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html"
1739        target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">the matplotlib
1740        documentation</a>.
1741
1742        **Regarding `show_joint_dist`**: this argument specifies whether we
1743        wish to plot the p-value of the *joint* distribution, or the p-value of
1744        the probability of a single parameter lying within the bounds projected
1745        onto a parameter axis. For more details, see <a
1746        href="https://arxiv.org/abs/0906.0664" target="_blank" rel="noopener
1747        noreferrer">arXiv:0906.0664</a>, section 2.
1748        """
1749        super().__init__(
1750            options=options,
1751            wspace=wspace,
1752            hspace=hspace,
1753            contour_levels=contour_levels,
1754        )
1755        self.show_1d_curves = show_1d_curves
1756        self.show_joint_dist = show_joint_dist
1757        self._ndim = 2
1758
1759        if contour_levels_1d is None:
1760            self.contour_levels_1d = self.contour_levels
1761        else:
1762            self.contour_levels_1d = _parse_contour_levels(contour_levels_1d)
1763
1764        if contour_levels_2d is None:
1765            self.contour_levels_2d = self.contour_levels
1766        else:
1767            self.contour_levels_2d = _parse_contour_levels(contour_levels_2d)
1768
1769    def __getitem__(
1770        self,
1771        key: tuple[str, str],
1772    ):
1773        if not self.figure:
1774            raise EmptyFigureError
1775
1776        if not isinstance(key, tuple):
1777            raise TypeError(
1778                f"Incompatible type for element access: expected `tuple`, got `{type(key)}`"
1779            )
1780
1781        name1, name2 = key
1782
1783        if name1 not in self.names:
1784            raise ParameterNotFoundError(name1, self.names)
1785        if name2 not in self.names:
1786            raise ParameterNotFoundError(name2, self.names)
1787
1788        # edge case
1789        if not self.show_1d_curves and name1 == name2:
1790            return None
1791
1792        index1 = np.where(self.names == name1)
1793        index2 = np.where(self.names == name2)
1794
1795        if index1 < index2:
1796            index1, index2 = index2, index1
1797
1798        return self.axes[index1, index2][0, 0]
1799
1800    def legend(
1801        self,
1802        *args: Artist,
1803        overwrite: bool = False,
1804        loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = "upper right",
1805        bbox_to_anchor: Optional[Any] = None,
1806        **kwargs,
1807    ):
1808        """
1809        Creates a legend on the figure.
1810
1811        Parameters
1812        ----------
1813        *args
1814            any positional arguments for the legend
1815
1816        overwrite : bool, optional
1817            whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by `fitk` (default:
1818            False)
1819
1820        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
1821            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
1822            (default: 'upper right')
1823
1824        bbox_to_anchor : Any, optional
1825            the location of where to place the legend (default: None, picked by
1826            `fitk` based on information about the plot)
1827
1828        **kwargs
1829            any other keyword arguments for the legend
1830
1831        Returns
1832        -------
1833        Artist
1834            the legend that was drawn on the figure
1835
1836        Raises
1837        ------
1838        EmptyFigureError
1839            if `figure` is not set
1840        """
1841        if not self.figure:
1842            raise EmptyFigureError
1843
1844        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1845            # this will always exist since we can't plot < 2 parameters
1846            ax = self[self.names[0], self.names[1]]
1847            if not overwrite:
1848                if self.show_1d_curves:
1849                    i, j = 0, -1
1850                else:
1851                    i, j = 1, -2
1852
1853                bbox_to_anchor = (
1854                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1855                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1856                )
1857
1858                if ax.get_legend():
1859                    ax.get_legend().remove()
1860
1861                return ax.legend(
1862                    self.handles,
1863                    self.labels,
1864                    loc=loc,
1865                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1866                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
1867                    **kwargs,
1868                )
1869
1870            return ax.legend(
1871                *args,
1872                loc=loc,
1873                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1874                **kwargs,
1875            )
1876
1877    def set_title(
1878        self,
1879        *args,
1880        overwrite: bool = False,
1881        xscale: float = 0.5,
1882        yscale: float = 1.08,
1883        **kwargs,
1884    ):
1885        """
1886        Thin wrapper for setting the title of the figure with the correct
1887        options.
1888
1889        Parameters
1890        ----------
1891        *args
1892            any positional arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1893
1894        xscale : float, optional
1895            the x position of the title (default: `0.5`)
1896
1897        yscale : float, optional
1898            the y position of the title (default: `1.08`)
1899
1900        **kwargs
1901            any keyword arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1902
1903        Returns
1904        -------
1905        Artist
1906            the title that was drawn on the figure
1907
1908        Raises
1909        ------
1910        EmptyFigureError
1911            if `figure` is not set
1912        """
1913        if not self.figure:
1914            raise EmptyFigureError
1915
1916        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1917            if not overwrite:
1918                if self.show_1d_curves:
1919                    i, j = 0, -1
1920                else:
1921                    i, j = 1, -2
1922
1923                x, y = (
1924                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1925                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1926                )
1927
1928                return self.figure.suptitle(
1929                    *args,
1930                    x=x * xscale,
1931                    y=y * yscale,
1932                    **kwargs,
1933                )
1934
1935            return self.figure.suptitle(*args, **kwargs)
1936
1937    def draw(
1938        self,
1939        name1: str,
1940        name2: str,
1941        method: str,
1942        *args,
1943        **kwargs,
1944    ):
1945        """
1946        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis where the parameters
1947        `name1` and `name2` have already been plotted.
1948
1949        Parameters
1950        ----------
1951        name1 : str
1952            the name (label) of the first parameter where we want to draw
1953
1954        name2 : str
1955            the name (label) of the second parameter where we want to draw
1956
1957        method : str
1958            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as `plot`,
1959            `scatter`, etc.)
1960
1961        *args
1962            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
1963
1964        **kwargs
1965            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
1966
1967        Returns
1968        -------
1969        Artist
1970            the artist that was drawn on the axis
1971
1972        Raises
1973        ------
1974        EmptyFigureError
1975            if `figure` is not set
1976
1977        AttributeError
1978            if `method` is not a valid plotting method
1979        """
1980        if not hasattr(self[name1, name2], method):
1981            raise AttributeError(
1982                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
1983            )
1984
1985        # get the right color
1986        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1987            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1988            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1989
1990        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1991            # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection
1992            # of artists
1993            handles = getattr(self[name1, name2], method)(*args, **kwargs)
1994            if is_iterable(handles):
1995                for handle in handles:
1996                    if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1997                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1998                        self.handles.append(handle)
1999            else:
2000                if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
2001                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
2002                    self.handles.append(handles)
2003
2004        self[name1, name2].autoscale()
2005        self[name1, name2].relim()
2006        self[name1, name2].autoscale_view()
2007
2008        return handles
2009
2010    def plot(
2011        self,
2012        fisher: FisherMatrix,
2013        *args,
2014        mark_fiducials: Union[bool, dict] = False,
2015        **kwargs,
2016    ):
2017        r"""
2018        Plots the 2D contours (and optionally 1D curves) of the Fisher objects.
2019
2020        Parameters
2021        ----------
2022        fisher : FisherMatrix
2023            the Fisher object which we want to plot
2024
2025        mark_fiducials : bool or dict, optional
2026            whether or not the fiducials should be marked on the plots
2027            (default: False). If set to `True`, uses `linestyle='--'` and
2028            `color='black'` as the default. If a dictionary, accepts the same
2029            keyword arguments as <a
2030            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline.html#matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline"
2031            target="_blank" rel="noreferrer
2032            noopener">`matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline`</a>.  If an empty
2033            dictionary, uses the default style (determined automatically).
2034
2035        **kwargs
2036            any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as `plot_curve_2d`)
2037
2038        Returns
2039        -------
2040        None
2041
2042        Examples
2043        --------
2044        Define a Fisher matrix:
2045        >>> m = FisherMatrix([[3, -2], [-2, 5]], names=['a', 'b'], latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'])
2046
2047        Initiate a figure:
2048        >>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)
2049
2050        Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:
2051        >>> fig.plot(m)
2052
2053        Save it to a file:
2054        >>> fig.savefig(
2055        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure2d_plot_example.png",
2056        ... dpi=150)
