2059        """
2060        size = len(fisher)
2061
2062        if size < 2:
2063            raise ValueError("Unable to make a 2D plot with < 2 parameters")
2064
2065        if self.names is not None:
2066            # make sure they have the same names; if not, raise an error
2067            if set(self.names) != set(fisher.names):
2068                raise ValueError(
2069                    f"The Fisher object names ({fisher.names}) "
2070                    f"do not match those on the figure ({self.names})"
2071                )
2072
2073            # otherwise, we reshuffle them
2074            fisher = fisher.sort(key=self.names)
2075
2076        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
2077        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
2078        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
2079            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
2080            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
2081
2082        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
2083            # general figure setup
2084            if self.figure:
2085                fig = self.figure
2086                ax = self.axes
2087            else:
2088                fig = plt.figure(
2089                    figsize=(2 * size, 2 * size),
2090                    clear=True,
2091                )
2092                ax = fig.add_gridspec(
2093                    nrows=size,
2094                    ncols=size,
2095                    hspace=self.hspace,
2096                    wspace=self.wspace,
2097                ).subplots(
2098                    sharex="col",
2099                    sharey=False,
2100                )
2101
2102            # set automatic limits
2103            _set_limits_2d(ax=ax, size=size)
2104
2105            # flag for whether the current artist has already been added to the
2106            # legend handle
2107            added = False
2108            # loop over the parameters
2109            for i, j in product(range(len(fisher.names)), repeat=2):
2110                namey, latex_namey, namex, latex_namex = (
2111                    fisher.names[i],
2112                    fisher.latex_names[i],
2113                    fisher.names[j],
2114                    fisher.latex_names[j],
2115                )
2116                # labels for 2D contours (increasing y)
2117                if i > 0 and j == 0:
2118                    ax[i, j].set_ylabel(latex_namey)
2119
2120                # labels for 2D contours (increasing x)
2121                if i == size - 1:
2122                    ax[i, j].set_xlabel(latex_namex)
2123
2124                # removing any unnecessary axes from the gridspec
2125                if i < j and self.figure is None:
2126                    # calling `remove()` is better than `axis("off")` because
2127                    # then we obtain the proper bounding box
2128                    try:
2129                        ax[i, j].remove()
2130                    except KeyError:
2131                        pass
2132
2133                # plotting the 2D contours
2134                elif i > j:
2135                    # plot 1-sigma 2D curves
2136                    # NOTE this is the "68% of the probability of a
2137                    # single parameter lying within the bounds projected
2138                    # onto a parameter axis"
2139                    _, __, handle = plot_curve_2d(
2140                        fisher,
2141                        namex,
2142                        namey,
2143                        ax=ax[i, j],
2144                        scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[0][0]
2145                        if not self.show_joint_dist
2146                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[0][0])),
2147                        fill=False,
2148                        zorder=20,
2149                        **kwargs,
2150                    )
2151
2152                    if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
2153                        self.handles.append(handle)
2154                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
2155                        added = True
2156
2157                    # same thing, but shaded
2158                    plot_curve_2d(
2159                        fisher,
2160                        namex,
2161                        namey,
2162                        ax=ax[i, j],
2163                        scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[0][0]
2164                        if not self.show_joint_dist
2165                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[0][0])),
2166                        fill=True,
2167                        alpha=self.contour_levels_2d[0][1],
2168                        ec=None,
2169                        zorder=20,
2170                        **kwargs,
2171                    )
2172
2173                    for index in range(1, len(self.contour_levels_2d)):
2174                        # the 2-sigma
2175                        plot_curve_2d(
2176                            fisher,
2177                            namex,
2178                            namey,
2179                            ax=ax[i, j],
2180                            scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[index][0]
2181                            if not self.show_joint_dist
2182                            else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[index][0])),
2183                            fill=False,
2184                            zorder=20,
2185                            **kwargs,
2186                        )
2187
2188                        # same thing, but shaded
2189                        plot_curve_2d(
2190                            fisher,
2191                            namex,
2192                            namey,
2193                            ax=ax[i, j],
2194                            scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[index][0]
2195                            if not self.show_joint_dist
2196                            else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[index][0])),
2197                            fill=True,
2198                            alpha=self.contour_levels_2d[index][1],
2199                            ec=None,
2200                            zorder=20,
2201                            **kwargs,
2202                        )
2203
2204                if i == j:
2205                    # plotting the 1D Gaussians
2206                    if self.show_1d_curves is True:
2207                        plot_curve_1d(
2208                            fisher,
2209                            namex,
2210                            ax=ax[i, i],
2211                            **kwargs,
2212                        )
2213
2214                        for contour_level in self.contour_levels_1d:
2215                            _add_shading_1d(
2216                                fisher.fiducials[i],
2217                                fisher.constraints(
2218                                    name=namex,
2219                                    marginalized=True,
2220                                )[0],
2221                                level=contour_level[0],
2222                                ax=ax[i, i],
2223                                alpha=contour_level[1],
2224                                **kwargs,
2225                            )
2226
2227                    else:
2228                        if self.figure is None:
2229                            try:
2230                                ax[i, i].remove()
2231                            except KeyError:
2232                                pass
2233
2234            # set automatic limits
2235            _rescale_limits_2d(ax=ax, size=size)
2236
2237            # marking the fiducials
2238            _mark_fiducials(
2239                fisher=fisher,
2240                ax=ax,
2241                size=size,
2242                mark_fiducials=mark_fiducials,
2243            )
2244
2245        self._figure = fig
2246        self._axes = ax
2247        self._names = fisher.names
2248
2249
2250def _get_chisq(
2251    sigma: float = 1,
2252    df: int = 2,
2253):
2254    r"""
2255    Returns $\Delta \chi^2$.
2256    To obtain the scaling coefficient $\alpha$, just take the square root of
2257    the output.
2258
2259    Parameters
2260    ----------
2261    sigma : float = 1
2262        the error on the parameter
2263
2264    df : int = 2
2265        the number of degrees of freedom
2266
2267    Returns
2268    -------
2269    float
2270    """
2271    return chi2.ppf(norm.cdf(sigma) - norm.cdf(-sigma), df=df)
2272
2273
2274def _add_plot_1d(
2275    fiducial: float,
2276    sigma: float,
2277    ax: Optional[Axes] = None,
2278    **kwargs,
2279) -> tuple[Figure, Axes, Artist]:
2280    """
2281    Adds a 1D Gaussian with marginalized constraints `sigma` close to fiducial
2282    value `fiducial` to axis `ax`.
2283    """
2284    if ax is None:
2285        _, ax = plt.subplots()
2286
2287    x = np.linspace(
2288        fiducial - 4 * sigma,
2289        fiducial + 4 * sigma,
2290        100,
2291    )
2292
2293    (handle,) = ax.plot(
2294        x,
2295        [norm.pdf(_, loc=fiducial, scale=sigma) for _ in x],
2296        **kwargs,
2297    )
2298
2299    return (ax.get_figure(), ax, handle)
2300
2301
2302def _add_shading_1d(
2303    fiducial: float,
2304    sigma: float,
2305    ax: Optional[Axes] = None,
2306    level: float = 1,
2307    **kwargs,
2308) -> tuple[Figure, Axes]:
2309    """
2310    Add shading to a 1D axes.
2311    """
2312    if ax is None:
2313        _, ax = plt.subplots()
2314
2315    # keyword args which have no effect on the plotting
2316    unused_kwargs = [
2317        "lw",
2318        "linewidth",
2319        "ec",
2320        "edgecolor",
2321        "fc",
2322        "facecolor",
2323    ]
2324    for kwarg in unused_kwargs:
2325        kwargs.pop(kwarg, None)
2326
2327    # the kwarg `color` supersedes `facecolor`, hence we need to remove it from
2328    # the passed kwargs, and call `fill_between` with `facecolor=color`
2329    color = kwargs.pop("color", None)
2330
2331    x = np.ndarray.flatten(
2332        np.linspace(
2333            fiducial - level * sigma,
2334            fiducial + level * sigma,
2335            100,
2336        )
2337    )
2338
2339    ax.fill_between(
2340        x,
2341        np.ndarray.flatten(
2342            np.array([norm.pdf(_, loc=fiducial, scale=sigma) for _ in x])
2343        ),
2344        edgecolor=None,
2345        facecolor=color,
2346        **kwargs,
2347    )
2348
2349    return (ax.get_figure(), ax)
2350
2351
2352def plot_curve_1d(
2353    fisher: FisherMatrix,
2354    name: str,
2355    ax: Optional[Axes] = None,
2356    **kwargs,
2357) -> tuple[Figure, Axes, Artist]:
2358    r"""
2359    Plots a 1D curve (usually marginalized Gaussian) from a Fisher object.
2360
2361    Parameters
2362    ----------
2363    fisher : FisherMatrix
2364        the Fisher matrix which we want to plot
2365
2366    name : str
2367        the name of the parameter which we want to plot
2368
2369    ax : matplotlib.axes.Axes, optional
2370        the axis on which we want to plot the contour (default: None). If None,
2371        plots to a new figure.
2372
2373    **kwargs
2374        any keyword arguments passed to <a
2375        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.plot.html"
2376        target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">`matplotlib.pyplot.plot`</a>.
2377
2378    Returns
2379    -------
2380    A 3-tuple `(Figure, Axes, Artist)`
2381        The figure and the axis on which the artist was drawn on, as well as
2382        the artist itself.
2383
2384    Examples
2385    --------
2386    Define a Fisher matrix:
2387    >>> m = FisherMatrix(
2388    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
2389    ... names=['a', 'b'],
2390    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
2391    ... )
2392
2393    Draw the marginalized parameter `a`:
2394    >>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_1d(m, name='a', ls='--', color='red')
2395
2396    Save it to a file:
2397    >>> fig.savefig(
2398    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "plot_curve_1d_example1.png",
2399    ... dpi=100)

2402    """
2403    if ax is None:
2404        _, ax = plt.subplots()
2405
2406    fid = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)]
2407    sigma = fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True)
2408
2409    return _add_plot_1d(fid, sigma, ax=ax, **kwargs)
2410
2411
2412def plot_curve_2d(
2413    fisher: FisherMatrix,
2414    name1: str,
2415    name2: str,
2416    ax: Optional[Axes] = None,
2417    scaling_factor: float = 1,
2418    **kwargs,
2419) -> tuple[Figure, Axes, Artist]:
2420    r"""
2421    Plots a 2D curve (usually ellipse) from two parameters of a Fisher object.
2422
2423    Parameters
2424    ----------
2425    fisher : FisherMatrix
2426        the Fisher matrix which we want to plot
2427
2428    name1 : str
2429        the name of the first parameter which we want to plot
2430
2431    name2 : str
2432        the name of the second parameter which we want to plot
2433
2434    ax : matplotlib.axes.Axes, optional
2435        the axis on which we want to plot the contour (default: None). If None,
2436        plots to a new figure.
2437
2438    **kwargs
2439        any keyword arguments passed to <a
2440        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.patches.Ellipse.html"
2441        target="_blank" rel="noopener
2442        noreferrer">`matplotlib.patches.Ellipse`</a>.
2443
2444    Returns
2445    -------
2446    A 3-tuple `(Figure, Axes, Artist)`
2447        The figure and the axis on which the artist was drawn on, as well as
2448        the artist itself.
2449
2450    Examples
2451    --------
2452    Define a Fisher matrix:
2453    >>> m = FisherMatrix(
2454    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
2455    ... names=['a', 'b'],
2456    ... fiducials=[1, -2],
2457    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
2458    ... )
2459
2460    Draw the 1$\sigma$ contour of the parameter combination `a`, `b`:
2461    >>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_2d(m, name1='a', name2='b', ls='--', color='red', fill=False)
2462
2463    Rescale the view a bit:
2464    >>> _ = ax.autoscale()
2465    >>> _ = ax.relim()
2466    >>> _ = ax.autoscale_view()
2467
2468    Save it to a file:
2469    >>> fig.savefig(
2470    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "plot_curve_2d_example1.png",
2471    ... dpi=100)

AQMARAAACBgCIAAAAABQwAEAAAIGAIgAABAwBAAAQAAAoYACAAAEDAEQAAAgIAhAAIAAAQMARAAACBgCIAAAAABQwAEAAAIGAIgAABAwBAAAQAAAoYACAAAEDAEQAAAgIAhAAIAAAQMARAAACBgCIAAAAABQwAEAAAImP8DRx0aJ3sVAw0AAAAASUVORK5CYII=">
2474
2475    Notes
2476    -----
2477    The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
2478    """
2479    if ax is None:
2480        _, ax = plt.subplots()
2481
2482    fidx = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name1)]
2483    fidy = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name2)]
2484
2485    a, b, angle = _get_ellipse(fisher, name1, name2)
2486
2487    patch = ax.add_patch(
2488        Ellipse(
2489            xy=(fidx, fidy),
2490            width=2 * a * scaling_factor,
2491            height=2 * b * scaling_factor,
2492            angle=angle,
2493            **kwargs,
2494        ),
2495    )
2496
2497    return (ax.get_figure(), ax, patch)
2498
2499
2500def _get_ellipse(
2501    fm: FisherMatrix,
2502    name1: str,
2503    name2: str,
2504) -> tuple[float, float, float]:
2505    """
2506    Constructs parameters for a Gaussian ellipse from the names.
2507    """
2508    if name1 == name2:
2509        raise ValueError("Names must be different")
2510
2511    # the inverse
2512    inv = FisherMatrix(fm.inverse(), names=fm.names)
2513
2514    sigmax2 = inv[name1, name1]
2515    sigmay2 = inv[name2, name2]
2516    sigmaxy = inv[name1, name2]
2517
2518    # basically the eigenvalues of the submatrix
2519    a = np.sqrt(
2520        (sigmax2 + sigmay2) / 2 + np.sqrt((sigmax2 - sigmay2) ** 2 / 4 + sigmaxy**2)
2521    )
2522
2523    b = np.sqrt(
2524        (sigmax2 + sigmay2) / 2 - np.sqrt((sigmax2 - sigmay2) ** 2 / 4 + sigmaxy**2)
2525    )
2526
2527    angle = np.rad2deg(
2528        np.arctan2(
2529            2 * sigmaxy,
2530            sigmax2 - sigmay2,
2531        )
2532        / 2
2533    )
2534
2535    return a, b, angle
2536
2537
2538def _mark_fiducial_1d(
2539    fisher: FisherMatrix,
2540    name: str,
2541    ax: Axes,
2542    **kwargs,
2543):
2544    # always put the fiducials on top (unless specified otherwise)
2545    zorder = kwargs.pop("zorder", 999)
2546
2547    ax.axvline(
2548        fisher.fiducials[np.where(name == fisher.names)][0],
2549        0,
2550        1,
2551        zorder=zorder,
2552        **kwargs,
2553    )
2554
2555
2556def _mark_fiducial_2d(
2557    fisher: FisherMatrix,
2558    name1: str,
2559    name2: str,
2560    ax: Axes,
2561    **kwargs,
2562):
2563    # always put the fiducials on top (unless specified otherwise)
2564    zorder = kwargs.pop("zorder", 999)
2565
2566    index1 = np.where(fisher.names == name1)[0]
2567    index2 = np.where(fisher.names == name2)[0]
2568    fiducial1 = fisher.fiducials[index1]
2569    fiducial2 = fisher.fiducials[index2]
2570
2571    ax.axhline(
2572        fiducial1,
2573        0,
2574        1,
2575        zorder=zorder,
2576        **kwargs,
2577    )
2578
2579    ax.axvline(
2580        fiducial2,
2581        0,
2582        1,
2583        zorder=zorder,
2584        **kwargs,
2585    )
2586

2588def _parse_contour_levels(contour_levels: Sequence[tuple[float, float]]):
2589    try:
2590        contour_levels = [
2591            (float(level), float(alpha)) for level, alpha in contour_levels
2592        ]
2593    except Exception as exc:
2594        raise ValueError(
2595            f"The object {contour_levels} cannot be converted to a list of 2-tuples"
2596        ) from exc
2597    for level, alpha in contour_levels:
2598        if level < 0:
2599            raise ValueError(f"Negative contour level found in: {contour_levels}")
2600        if not 0 <= alpha <= 1:
2601            raise ValueError(
2602                f"Opacity value outside of (0, 1) found in: {contour_levels}"
2603            )
2604
2605    return contour_levels

class FisherBarFigure(_FisherBaseFigure): 
 710class FisherBarFigure(_FisherBaseFigure):
 711    """
 712    Container for plotting single-axis bar-like figures
 713    (`plot_absolute_constraints` and `plot_relative_constraints`)
 714    """
 715
 716    def _parse_fractional_constraints(
 717        self,
 718        args: Sequence[FisherMatrix],
 719        marginalized: bool = True,
 720        colors: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 721        labels: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 722        values_label: Optional[str] = None,
 723        percent: bool = False,
 724        space: float = 0.3,
 725        scale: str = "linear",
 726    ):
 727        # error handling
 728        if not 0 <= space <= 1:
 729            raise ValueError("The value of `space` must be in the open interval (0, 1)")
 730
 731        allowed_scales = ["linear", "log", "symlog"]
 732        if scale not in allowed_scales:
 733            raise ValueError(f"The value of `scale` must be one of: {allowed_scales}")
 734
 735        for arg in args:
 736            if set(args[0].names) != set(arg.names):
 737                raise MismatchingValuesError(
 738                    "parameter name",
 739                    args[0].names,
 740                    arg.names,
 741                )
 742
 743        # reordering to match the first one
 744        args = [arg.sort(key=args[0].names) for arg in args]
 745
 746        # total number of parameters in the Fisher objects
 747        size = len(args[0])
 748
 749        # the width or height of all columns for a single parameter
 750        total_space = 1 - space
 751
 752        # the width or height of a single column for a single parameter
 753        space_per_object = total_space / len(args)
 754
 755        if not colors:
 756            colors = list(islice(self.current_color, len(args)))  # type: ignore
 757        elif len(colors) != len(args):
 758            raise MismatchingSizeError(colors, args)
 759
 760        if not labels:
 761            labels = [""] * len(args)
 762        elif len(labels) != len(args):
 763            raise MismatchingSizeError(labels, args)
 764
 765        if not values_label:
 766            if percent:
 767                values_label = r"$\sigma / \theta_\mathrm{fid}\ (\%)$"
 768            else:
 769                values_label = r"$\sigma / \theta_\mathrm{fid}$"
 770
 771        return _TempContainer(
 772            labels,
 773            colors,  # type: ignore
 774            [
 775                [
 776                    _ - total_space / 2 + (2 * index + 1) * space_per_object / 2
 777                    for _ in range(size)
 778                ]
 779                for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 780            ],
 781            [
 782                np.array(
 783                    [
 784                        arg.constraints(name=_, marginalized=marginalized)[0]
 785                        for _ in arg.names
 786                    ]
 787                )
 788                / np.array(
 789                    [
 790                        np.abs(fid) if not np.isclose(fid, 0) else 1
 791                        for fid in arg.fiducials
 792                    ]
 793                )
 794                for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 795            ],
 796            space_per_object=space_per_object,
 797            values_label=values_label,
 798            scale=scale,
 799        )
 800
 801    def plot_absolute_constraints(
 802        self,
 803        args: Sequence[FisherMatrix],
 804        kind: str,
 805        marginalized: bool = True,
 806        colors: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 807        labels: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 808        values_label: Optional[str] = None,
 809        scale: str = "linear",
 810        space: float = 0.3,
 811        capsize: Optional[float] = None,
 812        **kwargs,
 813    ):
 814        r"""
 815        Makes a plot of the constraints of the Fisher matrices
 816
 817        Parameters
 818        ----------
 819        args : array_like of FisherMatrix
 820            the Fisher matrices for which we want to plot the constraints
 821
 822        kind : str, {'bar', 'barh', 'errorbar'}
 823            the kind of plot we want (vertical bar, horizontal bar, errorbar)
 824
 825        marginalized : bool, optional
 826            whether the marginalized or the unmarginalized constraints should
 827            be plotted (default: True)
 828
 829        colors : array_like of str, optional
 830            the colors to use for the plotting (default: default matplotlib
 831            colors)
 832
 833        labels : array_like of str, optional
 834            the labels for the Fisher matrices (default: None)
 835
 836        values_label : str, optional
 837            the label for the axis containing the constraints (default:
 838            `$\theta_\mathrm{fid}$`)
 839
 840        scale : str, {'linear', 'log'}
 841            the scale used for the y axis (default: 'linear')
 842
 843        space : float, optional
 844            the space reserved between the bars (default: 0.3)
 845
 846        capsize : float, optional
 847            the width of the errorbars (default: none, that is, determined
 848            automatically)
 849
 850        **kwargs
 851            any keyword arguments passed to <a
 852            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.bar.html"
 853            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer
 854            noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.bar`</a>, or <a
 855            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.barh.html"
 856            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer
 857            noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.barh`</a>, or <a
 858            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.errorbar.html"
 859            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer
 860            noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.errorbar`</a>.
 861        Returns
 862        -------
 863        None
 864
 865        Examples
 866        --------
 867        Define some Fisher matrices:
 868        >>> fm1 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2, 3]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.3, 0.7, 0.96])
 869        >>> fm2 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([4, 5, 6]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.35, 0.67, 0.9])
 870
 871        Make a vertical bar plot:
 872        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
 873        >>> fig.plot_absolute_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'bar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
 874        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()
 875
 876        Save it to a file:
 877        >>> fig.savefig(
 878        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_absolute_constraints_bar.png",
 879        ... dpi=150)
 880

 895        Make an errobar plot:
 896        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
 897        >>> fig.plot_absolute_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'errorbar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'], capsize=4)
 898        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()
 899
 900        Save it to a file:
 901        >>> fig.savefig(
 902        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_absolute_constraints_errorbar.png",
 903        ... dpi=150)

 906        """
 907        size = len(args[0])
 908        latex_names = args[0].latex_names
 909
 910        # error handling
 911        if not 0 <= space <= 1:
 912            raise ValueError("The value of `space` must be in the open interval (0, 1)")
 913
 914        allowed_scales = ["linear", "log"]
 915        if scale not in allowed_scales:
 916            raise ValueError(f"The value of `scale` must be one of: {allowed_scales}")
 917
 918        for arg in args:
 919            if set(args[0].names) != set(arg.names):
 920                raise MismatchingValuesError(
 921                    "parameter name",
 922                    args[0].names,
 923                    arg.names,
 924                )
 925
 926        # reordering to match the first one
 927        args = [arg.sort(key=args[0].names) for arg in args]
 928
 929        # the width or height of all columns for a single parameter
 930        total_space = 1 - space
 931
 932        # the width or height of a single column for a single parameter
 933        space_per_object = total_space / len(args)
 934
 935        if not colors:
 936            colors = list(islice(self.current_color, len(args)))  # type: ignore
 937        elif len(colors) != len(args):
 938            raise MismatchingSizeError(colors, args)
 939
 940        if not labels:
 941            labels = [""] * len(args)
 942        elif len(labels) != len(args):
 943            raise MismatchingSizeError(labels, args)
 944
 945        if not values_label:
 946            values_label = r"$\theta_\mathrm{fid}$"
 947
 948        x_array = [
 949            [
 950                _ - total_space / 2 + (2 * index + 1) * space_per_object / 2
 951                for _ in range(size)
 952            ]
 953            for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 954        ]
 955        y_array = [arg.fiducials for arg in args]
 956        yerr_array = [
 957            np.array(
 958                [
 959                    arg.constraints(name=_, marginalized=marginalized)[0]
 960                    for _ in arg.names
 961                ]
 962            )
 963            for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 964        ]
 965
 966        # TODO: maybe put this in a class so validation is easier
 967        options = {
 968            "bar": {
 969                "parameters_scale": "x",
 970                "values_scale": "y",
 971                "error_name": "yerr",
 972                "extra_kwargs": {
 973                    "capsize": total_space * 60 / len(args) / size,
 974                    "width": space_per_object,
 975                },
 976            },
 977            "barh": {
 978                "parameters_scale": "y",
 979                "values_scale": "x",
 980                "error_name": "xerr",
 981                "extra_kwargs": {
 982                    "capsize": total_space * 60 / len(args) / size,
 983                    "height": space_per_object,
 984                },
 985            },
 986            "errorbar": {
 987                "parameters_scale": "x",
 988                "values_scale": "y",
 989                "error_name": "yerr",
 990                "extra_kwargs": {
 991                    "capsize": total_space * 120 / len(args) / size,
 992                    "ls": kwargs.pop("ls", ""),
 993                    "marker": kwargs.pop("marker", "o"),
 994                },
 995            },
 996        }
 997
 998        if capsize is not None:
 999            options[kind]["extra_kwargs"]["capsize"] = capsize  # type: ignore
1000
1001        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1002            fig, ax = plt.subplots()
1003            for color, label, x, y, yerr in zip(
1004                colors,  # type: ignore
1005                labels,
1006                x_array,
1007                y_array,
1008                yerr_array,
1009            ):
1010                getattr(ax, kind)(
1011                    x,
1012                    y,
1013                    color=color,
1014                    label=label,
1015                    **{options[kind]["error_name"]: yerr},
1016                    **options[kind]["extra_kwargs"],
1017                    **kwargs,
1018                )
1019
1020            ax.set_yscale(scale)
1021
1022            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticks')(range(size))
1023            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticklabels')(
1024                latex_names
1025            )
1026            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["values_scale"]}label')(values_label)
1027
1028        self._figure = fig
1029        self._axes = ax
1030
1031    def plot_relative_constraints(
1032        self,
1033        args: Sequence[FisherMatrix],
1034        kind: str,
1035        marginalized: bool = True,
1036        colors: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
1037        labels: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
1038        values_label: Optional[str] = None,
1039        scale: str = "linear",
1040        space: float = 0.3,
1041        percent: bool = False,
1042        **kwargs,
1043    ):
1044        r"""
1045        Makes a plot of the constraints (relative to the fiducial) of the
1046        Fisher matrices
1047
1048        Parameters
1049        ----------
1050        args : array_like of FisherMatrix
1051            the Fisher matrices for which we want to plot the constraints
1052
1053        kind : str, {'bar', 'barh', 'errorbar'}
1054            the kind of plot we want (vertical bar, horizontal bar, errorbar)
1055
1056        marginalized : bool, optional
1057            whether the marginalized or the unmarginalized constraints should
1058            be plotted (default: True)
1059
1060        colors : array_like of str, optional
1061            the colors to use for the plotting (default: default matplotlib
1062            colors)
1063
1064        labels : array_like of str, optional
1065            the labels for the Fisher matrices (default: None)
1066
1067        values_label : str, optional
1068            the label for the values, that is, the y axis (default: `$\sigma /
1069            \theta_\mathrm{fid}$` if `percent` is false, otherwise `$\sigma /
1070            \theta_\mathrm{fid}\ (\%)$`
1071
1072        scale : str, {'linear', 'log'}
1073            the scale used for the y axis (default: 'linear')
1074
1075        space : float, optional
1076            the space reserved between the bars (default: 0.3)
1077
1078        percent : bool, optional
1079            whether to plot in percentage units (default: false)
1080
1081        **kwargs
1082            any keyword arguments passed to
1083            <a
1084            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.bar.html"
1085            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.bar`</a>
1086
1087        Returns
1088        -------
1089        None
1090
1091        Examples
1092        --------
1093        Define some Fisher matrices:
1094        >>> fm1 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2, 3]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.3, 0.7, 0.96])
1095        >>> fm2 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([4, 5, 6]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.35, 0.67, 0.9])
1096
1097        Make a vertical bar plot:
1098        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
1099        >>> fig.plot_relative_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'bar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
1100        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()
1101
1102        Save it to a file:
1103        >>> fig.savefig(
1104        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_relative_constraints_bar.png",
1105        ... dpi=150)
1106

1109        Make a horizontal bar plot:
1110        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
1111        >>> fig.plot_relative_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'barh', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
1112        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()

1114        Save it to a file:
1115        >>> fig.savefig(

1117        ... dpi=150)

1120        """
1121        size = len(args[0])
1122        latex_names = args[0].latex_names
1123
1124        computed_parameters = self._parse_fractional_constraints(
1125            args,
1126            marginalized=marginalized,
1127            colors=colors,
1128            labels=labels,
1129            scale=scale,
1130            space=space,
1131            values_label=values_label,
1132            percent=percent,
1133        )
1134
1135        # TODO: maybe put this in a class so validation is easier
1136        options = {
1137            "bar": {
1138                "parameters_scale": "x",
1139                "values_scale": "y",
1140                "lines_prefix": "h",
1141                "extra_kwargs": {
1142                    "width": computed_parameters.space_per_object,
1143                },
1144            },
1145            "barh": {
1146                "parameters_scale": "y",
1147                "values_scale": "x",
1148                "lines_prefix": "v",
1149                "extra_kwargs": {
1150                    "height": computed_parameters.space_per_object,
1151                },
1152            },
1153        }
1154
1155        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1156            fig, ax = plt.subplots()
1157            for color, label, x, y in zip(
1158                computed_parameters.colors,
1159                computed_parameters.labels,
1160                computed_parameters.x_array,
1161                computed_parameters.y_array,
1162            ):
1163                getattr(ax, kind)(
1164                    x,
1165                    y * 100 if percent else y,
1166                    color=color,
1167                    label=label,
1168                    **options[kind]["extra_kwargs"],
1169                    **kwargs,
1170                )
1171                getattr(ax, kind)(
1172                    x,
1173                    -(y * 100 if percent else y),
1174                    color=color,
1175                    label=None,
1176                    **options[kind]["extra_kwargs"],
1177                    **kwargs,
1178                )
1179
1180            limits = getattr(ax, f'get_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}lim')()
1181
1182            getattr(ax, f'{options[kind]["lines_prefix"]}lines')(
1183                0, limits[0], limits[-1], color="black", ls="--"
1184            )
1185            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}lim')(*limits)
1186            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["values_scale"]}scale')(
1187                computed_parameters.scale
1188            )
1189
1190            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticks')(range(size))
1191            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticklabels')(
1192                latex_names
1193            )
1194            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["values_scale"]}label')(
1195                computed_parameters.values_label
1196            )
1197
1198        self._figure = fig
1199        self._axes = ax

Container for plotting single-axis bar-like figures (plot_absolute_constraints and plot_relative_constraints)

def plot_absolute_constraints( self, args: collections.abc.Sequence[fitk.tensors.FisherMatrix], kind: str, marginalized: bool = True, colors: Optional[collections.abc.Sequence[str]] = None, labels: Optional[collections.abc.Sequence[str]] = None, values_label: Optional[str] = None, scale: str = 'linear', space: float = 0.3, capsize: Optional[float] = None, **kwargs): 
 801    def plot_absolute_constraints(
 802        self,
 803        args: Sequence[FisherMatrix],
 804        kind: str,
 805        marginalized: bool = True,
 806        colors: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 807        labels: Optional[Sequence[str]] = None,
 808        values_label: Optional[str] = None,
 809        scale: str = "linear",
 810        space: float = 0.3,
 811        capsize: Optional[float] = None,
 812        **kwargs,
 813    ):
 814        r"""
 815        Makes a plot of the constraints of the Fisher matrices
 816
 817        Parameters
 818        ----------
 819        args : array_like of FisherMatrix
 820            the Fisher matrices for which we want to plot the constraints
 821
 822        kind : str, {'bar', 'barh', 'errorbar'}
 823            the kind of plot we want (vertical bar, horizontal bar, errorbar)
 824
 825        marginalized : bool, optional
 826            whether the marginalized or the unmarginalized constraints should
 827            be plotted (default: True)
 828
 829        colors : array_like of str, optional
 830            the colors to use for the plotting (default: default matplotlib
 831            colors)
 832
 833        labels : array_like of str, optional
 834            the labels for the Fisher matrices (default: None)
 835
 836        values_label : str, optional
 837            the label for the axis containing the constraints (default:
 838            `$\theta_\mathrm{fid}$`)
 839
 840        scale : str, {'linear', 'log'}
 841            the scale used for the y axis (default: 'linear')
 842
 843        space : float, optional
 844            the space reserved between the bars (default: 0.3)
 845
 846        capsize : float, optional
 847            the width of the errorbars (default: none, that is, determined
 848            automatically)
 849
 850        **kwargs
 851            any keyword arguments passed to <a
 852            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.bar.html"
 853            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer
 854            noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.bar`</a>, or <a
 855            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.barh.html"
 856            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer
 857            noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.barh`</a>, or <a
 858            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.errorbar.html"
 859            target="_blank" rel=noreferrer
 860            noopener>`matplotlib.pyplot.errorbar`</a>.
 861        Returns
 862        -------
 863        None
 864
 865        Examples
 866        --------
 867        Define some Fisher matrices:
 868        >>> fm1 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2, 3]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.3, 0.7, 0.96])
 869        >>> fm2 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([4, 5, 6]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.35, 0.67, 0.9])
 870
 871        Make a vertical bar plot:
 872        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
 873        >>> fig.plot_absolute_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'bar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
 874        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()
 875
 876        Save it to a file:
 877        >>> fig.savefig(
 878        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_absolute_constraints_bar.png",
 879        ... dpi=150)

 895        Make an errobar plot:
 896        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
 897        >>> fig.plot_absolute_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'errorbar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'], capsize=4)
 898        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()
 899
 900        Save it to a file:
 901        >>> fig.savefig(
 902        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_absolute_constraints_errorbar.png",
 903        ... dpi=150)

 906        """
 907        size = len(args[0])
 908        latex_names = args[0].latex_names
 909
 910        # error handling
 911        if not 0 <= space <= 1:
 912            raise ValueError("The value of `space` must be in the open interval (0, 1)")
 913
 914        allowed_scales = ["linear", "log"]
 915        if scale not in allowed_scales:
 916            raise ValueError(f"The value of `scale` must be one of: {allowed_scales}")
 917
 918        for arg in args:
 919            if set(args[0].names) != set(arg.names):
 920                raise MismatchingValuesError(
 921                    "parameter name",
 922                    args[0].names,
 923                    arg.names,
 924                )
 925
 926        # reordering to match the first one
 927        args = [arg.sort(key=args[0].names) for arg in args]
 928
 929        # the width or height of all columns for a single parameter
 930        total_space = 1 - space
 931
 932        # the width or height of a single column for a single parameter
 933        space_per_object = total_space / len(args)
 934
 935        if not colors:
 936            colors = list(islice(self.current_color, len(args)))  # type: ignore
 937        elif len(colors) != len(args):
 938            raise MismatchingSizeError(colors, args)
 939
 940        if not labels:
 941            labels = [""] * len(args)
 942        elif len(labels) != len(args):
 943            raise MismatchingSizeError(labels, args)
 944
 945        if not values_label:
 946            values_label = r"$\theta_\mathrm{fid}$"
 947
 948        x_array = [
 949            [
 950                _ - total_space / 2 + (2 * index + 1) * space_per_object / 2
 951                for _ in range(size)
 952            ]
 953            for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 954        ]
 955        y_array = [arg.fiducials for arg in args]
 956        yerr_array = [
 957            np.array(
 958                [
 959                    arg.constraints(name=_, marginalized=marginalized)[0]
 960                    for _ in arg.names
 961                ]
 962            )
 963            for index, arg in enumerate(args)
 964        ]
 965
 966        # TODO: maybe put this in a class so validation is easier
 967        options = {
 968            "bar": {
 969                "parameters_scale": "x",
 970                "values_scale": "y",
 971                "error_name": "yerr",
 972                "extra_kwargs": {
 973                    "capsize": total_space * 60 / len(args) / size,
 974                    "width": space_per_object,
 975                },
 976            },
 977            "barh": {
 978                "parameters_scale": "y",
 979                "values_scale": "x",
 980                "error_name": "xerr",
 981                "extra_kwargs": {
 982                    "capsize": total_space * 60 / len(args) / size,
 983                    "height": space_per_object,
 984                },
 985            },
 986            "errorbar": {
 987                "parameters_scale": "x",
 988                "values_scale": "y",
 989                "error_name": "yerr",
 990                "extra_kwargs": {
 991                    "capsize": total_space * 120 / len(args) / size,
 992                    "ls": kwargs.pop("ls", ""),
 993                    "marker": kwargs.pop("marker", "o"),
 994                },
 995            },
 996        }
 997
 998        if capsize is not None:
 999            options[kind]["extra_kwargs"]["capsize"] = capsize  # type: ignore
1000
1001        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1002            fig, ax = plt.subplots()
1003            for color, label, x, y, yerr in zip(
1004                colors,  # type: ignore
1005                labels,
1006                x_array,
1007                y_array,
1008                yerr_array,
1009            ):
1010                getattr(ax, kind)(
1011                    x,
1012                    y,
1013                    color=color,
1014                    label=label,
1015                    **{options[kind]["error_name"]: yerr},
1016                    **options[kind]["extra_kwargs"],
1017                    **kwargs,
1018                )
1019
1020            ax.set_yscale(scale)
1021
1022            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticks')(range(size))
1023            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticklabels')(
1024                latex_names
1025            )
1026            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["values_scale"]}label')(values_label)
1027
1028        self._figure = fig
1029        self._axes = ax

Makes a plot of the constraints of the Fisher matrices

Parameters
  • args (array_like of FisherMatrix): the Fisher matrices for which we want to plot the constraints
  • kind (str, {'bar', 'barh', 'errorbar'}): the kind of plot we want (vertical bar, horizontal bar, errorbar)
  • marginalized (bool, optional): whether the marginalized or the unmarginalized constraints should be plotted (default: True)
  • colors (array_like of str, optional): the colors to use for the plotting (default: default matplotlib colors)
  • labels (array_like of str, optional): the labels for the Fisher matrices (default: None)
  • values_label (str, optional): the label for the axis containing the constraints (default: $\theta_\mathrm{fid}$)
  • scale (str, {'linear', 'log'}): the scale used for the y axis (default: 'linear')
  • space (float, optional): the space reserved between the bars (default: 0.3)
  • capsize (float, optional): the width of the errorbars (default: none, that is, determined automatically)
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments passed to matplotlib.pyplot.bar, or matplotlib.pyplot.barh, or matplotlib.pyplot.errorbar.
Returns
  • None
Examples

Define some Fisher matrices:

>>> fm1 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2, 3]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.3, 0.7, 0.96])
>>> fm2 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([4, 5, 6]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.35, 0.67, 0.9])

Make a vertical bar plot:

>>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
>>> fig.plot_absolute_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'bar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
>>> _ = fig.figure.legend()

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_absolute_constraints_bar.png",
... dpi=150)

Make a horizontal bar plot:

>>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
>>> fig.plot_absolute_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'barh', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
>>> _ = fig.figure.legend()

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_absolute_constraints_barh.png",
... dpi=150)

Make an errobar plot:

>>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
>>> fig.plot_absolute_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'errorbar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'], capsize=4)
>>> _ = fig.figure.legend()

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_absolute_constraints_errorbar.png",
... dpi=150)

1109        Make a horizontal bar plot:
1110        >>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
1111        >>> fig.plot_relative_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'barh', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
1112        >>> _ = fig.figure.legend()
1113
1114        Save it to a file:
1115        >>> fig.savefig(
1116        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_relative_constraints_barh.png",
1117        ... dpi=150)

1120        """
1121        size = len(args[0])
1122        latex_names = args[0].latex_names
1123
1124        computed_parameters = self._parse_fractional_constraints(
1125            args,
1126            marginalized=marginalized,
1127            colors=colors,
1128            labels=labels,
1129            scale=scale,
1130            space=space,
1131            values_label=values_label,
1132            percent=percent,
1133        )
1134
1135        # TODO: maybe put this in a class so validation is easier
1136        options = {
1137            "bar": {
1138                "parameters_scale": "x",
1139                "values_scale": "y",
1140                "lines_prefix": "h",
1141                "extra_kwargs": {
1142                    "width": computed_parameters.space_per_object,
1143                },
1144            },
1145            "barh": {
1146                "parameters_scale": "y",
1147                "values_scale": "x",
1148                "lines_prefix": "v",
1149                "extra_kwargs": {
1150                    "height": computed_parameters.space_per_object,
1151                },
1152            },
1153        }
1154
1155        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1156            fig, ax = plt.subplots()
1157            for color, label, x, y in zip(
1158                computed_parameters.colors,
1159                computed_parameters.labels,
1160                computed_parameters.x_array,
1161                computed_parameters.y_array,
1162            ):
1163                getattr(ax, kind)(
1164                    x,
1165                    y * 100 if percent else y,
1166                    color=color,
1167                    label=label,
1168                    **options[kind]["extra_kwargs"],
1169                    **kwargs,
1170                )
1171                getattr(ax, kind)(
1172                    x,
1173                    -(y * 100 if percent else y),
1174                    color=color,
1175                    label=None,
1176                    **options[kind]["extra_kwargs"],
1177                    **kwargs,
1178                )
1179
1180            limits = getattr(ax, f'get_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}lim')()
1181
1182            getattr(ax, f'{options[kind]["lines_prefix"]}lines')(
1183                0, limits[0], limits[-1], color="black", ls="--"
1184            )
1185            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}lim')(*limits)
1186            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["values_scale"]}scale')(
1187                computed_parameters.scale
1188            )
1189
1190            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticks')(range(size))
1191            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["parameters_scale"]}ticklabels')(
1192                latex_names
1193            )
1194            getattr(ax, f'set_{options[kind]["values_scale"]}label')(
1195                computed_parameters.values_label
1196            )
1197
1198        self._figure = fig
1199        self._axes = ax

Makes a plot of the constraints (relative to the fiducial) of the Fisher matrices

Parameters
  • args (array_like of FisherMatrix): the Fisher matrices for which we want to plot the constraints
  • kind (str, {'bar', 'barh', 'errorbar'}): the kind of plot we want (vertical bar, horizontal bar, errorbar)
  • marginalized (bool, optional): whether the marginalized or the unmarginalized constraints should be plotted (default: True)
  • colors (array_like of str, optional): the colors to use for the plotting (default: default matplotlib colors)
  • labels (array_like of str, optional): the labels for the Fisher matrices (default: None)
  • values_label (str, optional): the label for the values, that is, the y axis (default: $\sigma / \theta_\mathrm{fid}$ if percent is false, otherwise $\sigma / \theta_\mathrm{fid}\ (\%)$
  • scale (str, {'linear', 'log'}): the scale used for the y axis (default: 'linear')
  • space (float, optional): the space reserved between the bars (default: 0.3)
  • percent (bool, optional): whether to plot in percentage units (default: false)
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments passed to matplotlib.pyplot.bar
Returns
  • None
Examples

Define some Fisher matrices:

>>> fm1 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2, 3]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.3, 0.7, 0.96])
>>> fm2 = FisherMatrix(np.diag([4, 5, 6]) * 1e3, names=["a", "b", "c"], latex_names=[r'$\Omega_\mathrm{m}$', '$h$', "$n_s$"], fiducials=[0.35, 0.67, 0.9])

Make a vertical bar plot:

>>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
>>> fig.plot_relative_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'bar', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
>>> _ = fig.figure.legend()

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_relative_constraints_bar.png",
... dpi=150)

Make a horizontal bar plot:

>>> fig = FisherBarFigure()
>>> fig.plot_relative_constraints([fm1, fm2], 'barh', labels=['Fisher 1', 'Fisher 2'])
>>> _ = fig.figure.legend()

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure_plot_relative_constraints_barh.png",
... dpi=150)

1250
1251    def __init__(
1252        self,
1253        options: Optional[dict] = None,
1254        max_cols: Optional[int] = None,
1255        hspace: float = 0.5,
1256        wspace: float = 0.1,
1257        contour_levels: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,
1258    ):
1259        """
1260        Constructor.
1261
1262        Parameters
1263        ----------
1264        options : dict, optional
1265            the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special
1266            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can
1267            be one of the outputs of <a
1268            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/style_api.html#matplotlib.style.matplotlib.style.available"
1269            target="_blank" rel="noopener
1270            noreferrer">`matplotlib.style.available`</a>, or a path to a file.
1271            If using a file, does not use the default rc parameters).
1272
1273        max_cols : int, optional
1274            the maximum number of columns in the final plot
1275
1276        hspace : float, optional
1277            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1278            as a fraction of the average axis height.
1279
1280        wspace : float, optional
1281            The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1282            as a fraction of the average axis width.
1283
1284        contour_levels : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1285            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded, along with
1286            the associated opacity (default: None). If not specified, defaults
1287            to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1288
1289        Notes
1290        -----
1291        For the style sheet reference, please consult <a
1292        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html"
1293        target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">the matplotlib
1294        documentation</a>.
1295        """
1296        super().__init__(
1297            options=options,
1298            wspace=wspace,
1299            hspace=hspace,
1300            contour_levels=contour_levels,
1301        )
1302        self.max_cols = max_cols
1303        self._ndim = 1
1304        self._hspace = hspace
1305        self._wspace = wspace
1306
1307    def __getitem__(
1308        self,
1309        key: str,
1310    ):
1311        """
1312        Returns the axis associated to the name `key`.
1313        """
1314        if not self.figure:
1315            raise EmptyFigureError
1316
1317        if key not in self.names:
1318            raise ParameterNotFoundError(key, self.names)
1319
1320        return self.axes.flat[np.where(self.names == key)][0]
1321
1322    def draw(
1323        self,
1324        name: str,
1325        method: str,
1326        *args,
1327        **kwargs,
1328    ):
1329        """
1330        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis where the parameter
1331        `name` has already been plotted.
1332
1333        Parameters
1334        ----------
1335        name : str
1336            the name (label) of the parameter where we want to draw
1337
1338        method : str
1339            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as <a
1340            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.plot.html"
1341            target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">`plot`</a>, <a
1342            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.scatter.html"
1343            target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">`scatter`</a>, etc.)
1344
1345        *args
1346            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
1347
1348        **kwargs
1349            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
1350
1351        Returns
1352        -------
1353        Artist
1354            the artist that was drawn on the axis
1355
1356        Raises
1357        ------
1358        EmptyFigureError
1359            if `figure` is not set
1360
1361        AttributeError
1362            if `method` is not a valid plotting method
1363        """
1364        if not hasattr(self[name], method):
1365            raise AttributeError(
1366                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
1367            )
1368
1369        # get the right color
1370        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1371            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1372            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1373
1374        # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection of
1375        # artists
1376        handles = getattr(self[name], method)(*args, **kwargs)
1377        if is_iterable(handles):
1378            for handle in handles:
1379                if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1380                    self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
1381                    self.handles.append(handle)
1382        else:
1383            if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1384                self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
1385                self.handles.append(handles)
1386
1387        self[name].autoscale()
1388        self[name].relim()
1389        self[name].autoscale_view()
1390
1391        return handles
1392
1393    def plot(
1394        self,
1395        fisher: FisherMatrix,
1396        *args,
1397        mark_fiducials: Union[bool, dict] = False,
1398        **kwargs,
1399    ):
1400        """
1401        Plots the 1D curves of the Fisher objects.
1402
1403        Parameters
1404        ----------
1405        fisher
1406            the Fisher object which we want to plot
1407
1408        mark_fiducials : bool or dict, optional
1409            whether or not the fiducials should be marked on the plots
1410            (default: False). If set to `True`, uses `linestyle='--'` and
1411            `color='black'` as the default. If a dictionary, accepts the same
1412            keyword arguments as <a
1413            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline.html#matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline"
1414            target="_blank" rel="noreferrer
1415            noopener">`matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline`</a>.  If an empty
1416            dictionary, uses the default style (determined automatically).
1417
1418        **kwargs
1419            any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as `plot_curve_1d`)
1420
1421        Returns
1422        -------
1423        None
1424        """
1425        size = len(fisher)
1426
1427        added = False
1428
1429        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
1430        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
1431        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1432            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1433            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1434
1435        if self.max_cols is not None and self.max_cols <= size:
1436            full = size % self.max_cols == 0
1437            layout = (
1438                size // self.max_cols if full else size // self.max_cols + 1,
1439                self.max_cols,
1440            )
1441        else:
1442            layout = 1, size
1443            full = True
1444
1445        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1446            # general figure setup
1447            if self.figure:
1448                fig = self.figure
1449                axes = self.axes
1450            else:
1451                fig = plt.figure(
1452                    clear=True,
1453                    figsize=(2 * layout[1], 2 * layout[0]),
1454                )
1455                gs = fig.add_gridspec(
1456                    nrows=layout[0],
1457                    ncols=layout[1],
1458                    hspace=self.hspace,
1459                    wspace=self.wspace,
1460                )
1461                axes = gs.subplots()
1462                if size == 1:
1463                    axes = np.array([axes])
1464
1465            for (index, name), latex_name in zip(
1466                enumerate(fisher.names),
1467                fisher.latex_names,
1468            ):
1469                ax = axes.flat[index]
1470
1471                _, __, handle = plot_curve_1d(fisher, name, ax, **kwargs)
1472
1473                if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
1474                    self.handles.append(handle)
1475                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1476                    added = True
1477
1478                for contour_level in self.contour_levels:
1479                    _add_shading_1d(
1480                        fisher.fiducials[index],
1481                        fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True),
1482                        ax,
1483                        level=contour_level[0],
1484                        alpha=contour_level[1],
1485                        **kwargs,
1486                    )
1487
1488                ax.autoscale()
1489                ax.set_xlabel(latex_name)
1490                ax.relim()
1491                ax.autoscale_view()
1492
1493                # the y axis should start at 0 since we're plotting a PDF
1494                ax.set_ylim(0, ax.get_ylim()[-1])
1495
1496                ax.set_yticks([])
1497
1498                # marking the fiducials
1499                if not mark_fiducials is False:
1500                    if mark_fiducials is True:
1501                        mark_fiducials = dict(linestyle="--", color="black")
1502
1503                    _mark_fiducial_1d(
1504                        fisher,
1505                        fisher.names[index],
1506                        ax,
1507                        **mark_fiducials,
1508                    )
1509
1510            # remove any axes which are not drawn
1511            if not full:
1512                for index in range(
1513                    size,
1514                    layout[0] * layout[1],
1515                ):
1516                    # it's simpler to turn off the axis, than completely remove
1517                    # it
1518                    axes.flat[index].axis("off")
1519
1520        self._figure = fig
1521        self._axes = axes
1522        self._names = fisher.names
1523
1524    def legend(
1525        self,
1526        *args: Artist,
1527        overwrite: bool = False,
1528        loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = "lower center",
1529        bbox_to_anchor: Any = (0.5, 1),
1530        **kwargs,
1531    ):
1532        """
1533        Creates a legend on the figure.
1534
1535        Parameters
1536        ----------
1537        *args
1538            any positional arguments for the legend
1539
1540        overwrite : bool, optional
1541            whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by `fitk` (default:
1542            False)
1543
1544        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
1545            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
1546            (default: 'lower center')
1547
1548        bbox_to_anchor : Any, optional
1549            the location of where to place the legend (default: `[0.5, 1]`)
1550
1551        **kwargs
1552            any other keyword arguments for the legend
1553
1554        Returns
1555        -------
1556        Artist
1557            the legend that was drawn on the figure
1558
1559        Raises
1560        ------
1561        EmptyFigureError
1562            if `figure` is not set
1563        """
1564        if not self.figure:
1565            raise EmptyFigureError
1566
1567        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1568            ax = self.axes.flat[0]
1569            if not overwrite:
1570                if ax.get_legend():
1571                    ax.get_legend().remove()
1572
1573                return ax.legend(
1574                    self.handles,
1575                    self.labels,
1576                    loc=loc,
1577                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1578                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
1579                    **kwargs,
1580                )
1581
1582            return ax.legend(
1583                *args,
1584                loc=loc,
1585                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1586                **kwargs,
1587            )

1593        y: float = 1.2,
1594        **kwargs,
1595    ):
1596        """
1597        Thin wrapper for setting the title of the figure with the correct
1598        options.
1599
1600        Parameters
1601        ----------

1604

1606            the x position of the title (default: `0.5`)
1607
1608        y : float, optional
1609            the y position of the title (default: `1.2`)
1610
1611        **kwargs
1612            any keyword arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1613
1614        Returns
1615        -------
1616        Artist
1617            the title that was drawn on the figure
1618
1619        Raises
1620        ------
1621        EmptyFigureError
1622            if `figure` is not set
1623        """
1624        if not self.figure:
1625            raise EmptyFigureError
1626

1628            return self.figure.suptitle(*args, x=x, y=y, **kwargs)

Container for easy access to elements in the 1D plot.

Examples

Define some Fisher matrices:

>>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )
>>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )

Instantiate a figure:

>>> fig = FisherFigure1D()

Draw marginalized 1D plots with the previously defined Fisher matrix:

>>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')

Add another plot with a different color and style:

>>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')

Draw some other stuff on it:

>>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red', label='curve')
>>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
>>> # artist, = fig['a'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
>>> # note that in this case, due to certain limitations, you need to
>>> # manually add the legend using a convenience function:
>>> # fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')

Add a legend:

>>> _ = fig.legend(ncol=3, loc='center')

Add a title:

>>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 1D plotting')

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure1d_example1.png",
... dpi=150)

Constructor.

Parameters
  • options (dict, optional): the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can be one of the outputs of matplotlib.style.available, or a path to a file. If using a file, does not use the default rc parameters).
  • max_cols (int, optional): the maximum number of columns in the final plot
  • hspace (float, optional): The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis height.
  • wspace (float, optional): The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis width.
  • contour_levels (array_like of 2-tuples, optional): the points at which the sigma level should be shaded, along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not specified, defaults to [(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)].
Notes

  • overwrite (bool, optional): whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by fitk (default: False)
  • loc (str or tuple of floats, optional): which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor (default: 'lower center')

  • **kwargs: any other keyword arguments for the legend
Returns
  • Artist: the legend that was drawn on the figure
Raises
  • EmptyFigureError: if figure is not set

1596        """
1597        Thin wrapper for setting the title of the figure with the correct
1598        options.
1599
1600        Parameters
1601        ----------
1602        *args
1603            any positional arguments to `figure.suptitle`

1605        x : float, optional
1606            the x position of the title (default: `0.5`)
1607
1608        y : float, optional
1609            the y position of the title (default: `1.2`)
1610
1611        **kwargs
1612            any keyword arguments to `figure.suptitle`

1615        -------

1626

class FisherFigure2D(_FisherMultipleAxesFigure): 
1631class FisherFigure2D(_FisherMultipleAxesFigure):
1632    r"""
1633    Container for easy access to elements in the 2D plot.
1634
1635    Examples
1636    --------
1637    Define some Fisher matrices:
1638    >>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
1639    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
1640    ... names=['a', 'b'],
1641    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
1642    ... )
1643    >>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
1644    ... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
1645    ... names=['a', 'b'],
1646    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
1647    ... )
1648
1649    Instantiate a figure:
1650    >>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)
1651
1652    Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:
1653    >>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')
1654
1655    Add a plot with a different color and style:
1656    >>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')
1657
1658    Draw some other stuff on it:
1659    >>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'b', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red', label='curve')
1660    >>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
1661    >>> # artist, = fig['a', 'b'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
1662    >>> # note that in this case, due to certain limitations, you need to
1663    >>> # manually add the legend using a convenience function:
1664    >>> # fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')
1665
1666    Add a legend:
1667    >>> _ = fig.legend()
1668
1669    Add a title:
1670    >>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 2D plotting')
1671
1672    Save it to a file:
1673    >>> fig.savefig(
1674    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure2d_example1.png",
1675    ... dpi=150)
