1678    """
1679
1680    def __init__(
1681        self,
1682        options: Optional[dict] = None,
1683        hspace: float = 0,
1684        wspace: float = 0,
1685        show_1d_curves: bool = False,
1686        show_joint_dist: bool = False,
1687        contour_levels: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,
1688        contour_levels_1d: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,
1689        contour_levels_2d: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,
1690    ):
1691        """
1692        Constructor.
1693
1694        Parameters
1695        ----------
1696        options : dict, optional
1697            the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special
1698            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can
1699            be one of the outputs of <a
1700            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/style_api.html#matplotlib.style.matplotlib.style.available"
1701            target="_blank" rel="noopener
1702            noreferrer">`matplotlib.style.available`</a>, or a path to a file.
1703            If using a file, does not use the default rc parameters).
1704
1705        hspace : float, optional
1706            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1707            as a fraction of the average axis height.
1708
1709        wspace : float, optional
1710            The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1711            as a fraction of the average axis width.
1712
1713        show_1d_curves : bool, optional
1714            whether the 1D marginalized curves should be plotted (default:
1715            False)
1716
1717        show_joint_dist : bool, optional
1718            whether to plot the isocontours of the joint distribution (default:
1719            False)
1720
1721        contour_levels : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1722            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded, along with
1723            the associated opacity (default: None). If not specified, defaults
1724            to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1725
1726        contour_levels_1d : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1727            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded (on the 1D
1728            plots), along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not
1729            specified, defaults to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1730
1731        contour_levels_2d : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1732            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded (on the 2D
1733            plots), along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not
1734            specified, defaults to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1735
1736        Notes
1737        -----
1738        For the style sheet reference, please consult <a
1739        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html"
1740        target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">the matplotlib
1741        documentation</a>.
1742
1743        **Regarding `show_joint_dist`**: this argument specifies whether we
1744        wish to plot the p-value of the *joint* distribution, or the p-value of
1745        the probability of a single parameter lying within the bounds projected
1746        onto a parameter axis. For more details, see <a
1747        href="https://arxiv.org/abs/0906.0664" target="_blank" rel="noopener
1748        noreferrer">arXiv:0906.0664</a>, section 2.
1749        """
1750        super().__init__(
1751            options=options,
1752            wspace=wspace,
1753            hspace=hspace,
1754            contour_levels=contour_levels,
1755        )
1756        self.show_1d_curves = show_1d_curves
1757        self.show_joint_dist = show_joint_dist
1758        self._ndim = 2
1759
1760        if contour_levels_1d is None:
1761            self.contour_levels_1d = self.contour_levels
1762        else:
1763            self.contour_levels_1d = _parse_contour_levels(contour_levels_1d)
1764
1765        if contour_levels_2d is None:
1766            self.contour_levels_2d = self.contour_levels
1767        else:
1768            self.contour_levels_2d = _parse_contour_levels(contour_levels_2d)
1769
1770    def __getitem__(
1771        self,
1772        key: tuple[str, str],
1773    ):
1774        if not self.figure:
1775            raise EmptyFigureError
1776
1777        if not isinstance(key, tuple):
1778            raise TypeError(
1779                f"Incompatible type for element access: expected `tuple`, got `{type(key)}`"
1780            )
1781
1782        name1, name2 = key
1783
1784        if name1 not in self.names:
1785            raise ParameterNotFoundError(name1, self.names)
1786        if name2 not in self.names:
1787            raise ParameterNotFoundError(name2, self.names)
1788
1789        # edge case
1790        if not self.show_1d_curves and name1 == name2:
1791            return None
1792
1793        index1 = np.where(self.names == name1)
1794        index2 = np.where(self.names == name2)
1795
1796        if index1 < index2:
1797            index1, index2 = index2, index1
1798
1799        return self.axes[index1, index2][0, 0]
1800
1801    def legend(
1802        self,
1803        *args: Artist,
1804        overwrite: bool = False,
1805        loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = "upper right",
1806        bbox_to_anchor: Optional[Any] = None,
1807        **kwargs,
1808    ):
1809        """
1810        Creates a legend on the figure.
1811
1812        Parameters
1813        ----------
1814        *args
1815            any positional arguments for the legend
1816
1817        overwrite : bool, optional
1818            whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by `fitk` (default:
1819            False)
1820
1821        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
1822            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
1823            (default: 'upper right')
1824
1825        bbox_to_anchor : Any, optional
1826            the location of where to place the legend (default: None, picked by
1827            `fitk` based on information about the plot)
1828
1829        **kwargs
1830            any other keyword arguments for the legend
1831
1832        Returns
1833        -------
1834        Artist
1835            the legend that was drawn on the figure
1836
1837        Raises
1838        ------
1839        EmptyFigureError
1840            if `figure` is not set
1841        """
1842        if not self.figure:
1843            raise EmptyFigureError
1844
1845        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1846            # this will always exist since we can't plot < 2 parameters
1847            ax = self[self.names[0], self.names[1]]
1848            if not overwrite:
1849                if self.show_1d_curves:
1850                    i, j = 0, -1
1851                else:
1852                    i, j = 1, -2
1853
1854                bbox_to_anchor = (
1855                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1856                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1857                )
1858
1859                if ax.get_legend():
1860                    ax.get_legend().remove()
1861
1862                return ax.legend(
1863                    self.handles,
1864                    self.labels,
1865                    loc=loc,
1866                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1867                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
1868                    **kwargs,
1869                )
1870
1871            return ax.legend(
1872                *args,
1873                loc=loc,
1874                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1875                **kwargs,
1876            )
1877
1878    def set_title(
1879        self,
1880        *args,
1881        overwrite: bool = False,
1882        xscale: float = 0.5,
1883        yscale: float = 1.08,
1884        **kwargs,
1885    ):
1886        """
1887        Thin wrapper for setting the title of the figure with the correct
1888        options.
1889
1890        Parameters
1891        ----------
1892        *args
1893            any positional arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1894
1895        xscale : float, optional
1896            the x position of the title (default: `0.5`)
1897
1898        yscale : float, optional
1899            the y position of the title (default: `1.08`)
1900
1901        **kwargs
1902            any keyword arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1903
1904        Returns
1905        -------
1906        Artist
1907            the title that was drawn on the figure
1908
1909        Raises
1910        ------
1911        EmptyFigureError
1912            if `figure` is not set
1913        """
1914        if not self.figure:
1915            raise EmptyFigureError
1916
1917        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1918            if not overwrite:
1919                if self.show_1d_curves:
1920                    i, j = 0, -1
1921                else:
1922                    i, j = 1, -2
1923
1924                x, y = (
1925                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1926                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1927                )
1928
1929                return self.figure.suptitle(
1930                    *args,
1931                    x=x * xscale,
1932                    y=y * yscale,
1933                    **kwargs,
1934                )
1935
1936            return self.figure.suptitle(*args, **kwargs)
1937
1938    def draw(
1939        self,
1940        name1: str,
1941        name2: str,
1942        method: str,
1943        *args,
1944        **kwargs,
1945    ):
1946        """
1947        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis where the parameters
1948        `name1` and `name2` have already been plotted.
1949
1950        Parameters
1951        ----------
1952        name1 : str
1953            the name (label) of the first parameter where we want to draw
1954
1955        name2 : str
1956            the name (label) of the second parameter where we want to draw
1957
1958        method : str
1959            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as `plot`,
1960            `scatter`, etc.)
1961
1962        *args
1963            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
1964
1965        **kwargs
1966            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
1967
1968        Returns
1969        -------
1970        Artist
1971            the artist that was drawn on the axis
1972
1973        Raises
1974        ------
1975        EmptyFigureError
1976            if `figure` is not set
1977
1978        AttributeError
1979            if `method` is not a valid plotting method
1980        """
1981        if not hasattr(self[name1, name2], method):
1982            raise AttributeError(
1983                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
1984            )
1985
1986        # get the right color
1987        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1988            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1989            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1990
1991        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1992            # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection
1993            # of artists
1994            handles = getattr(self[name1, name2], method)(*args, **kwargs)
1995            if is_iterable(handles):
1996                for handle in handles:
1997                    if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1998                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1999                        self.handles.append(handle)
2000            else:
2001                if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
2002                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
2003                    self.handles.append(handles)
2004
2005        self[name1, name2].autoscale()
2006        self[name1, name2].relim()
2007        self[name1, name2].autoscale_view()
2008
2009        return handles
2010
2011    def plot(
2012        self,
2013        fisher: FisherMatrix,
2014        *args,
2015        mark_fiducials: Union[bool, dict] = False,
2016        **kwargs,
2017    ):
2018        r"""
2019        Plots the 2D contours (and optionally 1D curves) of the Fisher objects.
2020
2021        Parameters
2022        ----------
2023        fisher : FisherMatrix
2024            the Fisher object which we want to plot
2025
2026        mark_fiducials : bool or dict, optional
2027            whether or not the fiducials should be marked on the plots
2028            (default: False). If set to `True`, uses `linestyle='--'` and
2029            `color='black'` as the default. If a dictionary, accepts the same
2030            keyword arguments as <a
2031            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline.html#matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline"
2032            target="_blank" rel="noreferrer
2033            noopener">`matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline`</a>.  If an empty
2034            dictionary, uses the default style (determined automatically).
2035
2036        **kwargs
2037            any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as `plot_curve_2d`)
2038
2039        Returns
2040        -------
2041        None
2042
2043        Examples
2044        --------
2045        Define a Fisher matrix:
2046        >>> m = FisherMatrix([[3, -2], [-2, 5]], names=['a', 'b'], latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'])
2047
2048        Initiate a figure:
2049        >>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)
2050
2051        Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:
2052        >>> fig.plot(m)
2053
2054        Save it to a file:
2055        >>> fig.savefig(
2056        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure2d_plot_example.png",
2057        ... dpi=150)
2058

2060        """
2061        size = len(fisher)
2062
2063        if size < 2:
2064            raise ValueError("Unable to make a 2D plot with < 2 parameters")
2065
2066        if self.names is not None:
2067            # make sure they have the same names; if not, raise an error
2068            if set(self.names) != set(fisher.names):
2069                raise ValueError(
2070                    f"The Fisher object names ({fisher.names}) "
2071                    f"do not match those on the figure ({self.names})"
2072                )
2073
2074            # otherwise, we reshuffle them
2075            fisher = fisher.sort(key=self.names)
2076
2077        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
2078        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
2079        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
2080            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
2081            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
2082
2083        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
2084            # general figure setup
2085            if self.figure:
2086                fig = self.figure
2087                ax = self.axes
2088            else:
2089                fig = plt.figure(
2090                    figsize=(2 * size, 2 * size),
2091                    clear=True,
2092                )
2093                ax = fig.add_gridspec(
2094                    nrows=size,
2095                    ncols=size,
2096                    hspace=self.hspace,
2097                    wspace=self.wspace,
2098                ).subplots(
2099                    sharex="col",
2100                    sharey=False,
2101                )
2102
2103            # set automatic limits
2104            _set_limits_2d(ax=ax, size=size)
2105
2106            # flag for whether the current artist has already been added to the
2107            # legend handle
2108            added = False
2109            # loop over the parameters
2110            for i, j in product(range(len(fisher.names)), repeat=2):
2111                namey, latex_namey, namex, latex_namex = (
2112                    fisher.names[i],
2113                    fisher.latex_names[i],
2114                    fisher.names[j],
2115                    fisher.latex_names[j],
2116                )
2117                # labels for 2D contours (increasing y)
2118                if i > 0 and j == 0:
2119                    ax[i, j].set_ylabel(latex_namey)
2120
2121                # labels for 2D contours (increasing x)
2122                if i == size - 1:
2123                    ax[i, j].set_xlabel(latex_namex)
2124
2125                # removing any unnecessary axes from the gridspec
2126                if i < j and self.figure is None:
2127                    # calling `remove()` is better than `axis("off")` because
2128                    # then we obtain the proper bounding box
2129                    try:
2130                        ax[i, j].remove()
2131                    except KeyError:
2132                        pass
2133
2134                # plotting the 2D contours
2135                elif i > j:
2136                    # plot 1-sigma 2D curves
2137                    # NOTE this is the "68% of the probability of a
2138                    # single parameter lying within the bounds projected
2139                    # onto a parameter axis"
2140                    _, __, handle = plot_curve_2d(
2141                        fisher,
2142                        namex,
2143                        namey,
2144                        ax=ax[i, j],
2145                        scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[0][0]
2146                        if not self.show_joint_dist
2147                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[0][0])),
2148                        fill=False,
2149                        zorder=20,
2150                        **kwargs,
2151                    )
2152
2153                    if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
2154                        self.handles.append(handle)
2155                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
2156                        added = True
2157
2158                    # same thing, but shaded
2159                    plot_curve_2d(
2160                        fisher,
2161                        namex,
2162                        namey,
2163                        ax=ax[i, j],
2164                        scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[0][0]
2165                        if not self.show_joint_dist
2166                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[0][0])),
2167                        fill=True,
2168                        alpha=self.contour_levels_2d[0][1],
2169                        ec=None,
2170                        zorder=20,
2171                        **kwargs,
2172                    )
2173
2174                    for index in range(1, len(self.contour_levels_2d)):
2175                        # the 2-sigma
2176                        plot_curve_2d(
2177                            fisher,
2178                            namex,
2179                            namey,
2180                            ax=ax[i, j],
2181                            scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[index][0]
2182                            if not self.show_joint_dist
2183                            else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[index][0])),
2184                            fill=False,
2185                            zorder=20,
2186                            **kwargs,
2187                        )
2188
2189                        # same thing, but shaded
2190                        plot_curve_2d(
2191                            fisher,
2192                            namex,
2193                            namey,
2194                            ax=ax[i, j],
2195                            scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[index][0]
2196                            if not self.show_joint_dist
2197                            else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[index][0])),
2198                            fill=True,
2199                            alpha=self.contour_levels_2d[index][1],
2200                            ec=None,
2201                            zorder=20,
2202                            **kwargs,
2203                        )
2204
2205                if i == j:
2206                    # plotting the 1D Gaussians
2207                    if self.show_1d_curves is True:
2208                        plot_curve_1d(
2209                            fisher,
2210                            namex,
2211                            ax=ax[i, i],
2212                            **kwargs,
2213                        )
2214
2215                        for contour_level in self.contour_levels_1d:
2216                            _add_shading_1d(
2217                                fisher.fiducials[i],
2218                                fisher.constraints(
2219                                    name=namex,
2220                                    marginalized=True,
2221                                )[0],
2222                                level=contour_level[0],
2223                                ax=ax[i, i],
2224                                alpha=contour_level[1],
2225                                **kwargs,
2226                            )
2227
2228                    else:
2229                        if self.figure is None:
2230                            try:
2231                                ax[i, i].remove()
2232                            except KeyError:
2233                                pass
2234
2235            # set automatic limits
2236            _rescale_limits_2d(ax=ax, size=size)
2237
2238            # marking the fiducials
2239            _mark_fiducials(
2240                fisher=fisher,
2241                ax=ax,
2242                size=size,
2243                mark_fiducials=mark_fiducials,
2244            )
2245
2246        self._figure = fig
2247        self._axes = ax
2248        self._names = fisher.names

Container for easy access to elements in the 2D plot.

Examples

Define some Fisher matrices:

>>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )
>>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )

Instantiate a figure:

>>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)

Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:

>>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')

Add a plot with a different color and style:

>>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')

Draw some other stuff on it:

>>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'b', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red', label='curve')
>>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
>>> # artist, = fig['a', 'b'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
>>> # note that in this case, due to certain limitations, you need to
>>> # manually add the legend using a convenience function:
>>> # fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')

Add a legend:

>>> _ = fig.legend()

Add a title:

>>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 2D plotting')

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure2d_example1.png",
... dpi=150)

FisherFigure2D( options: Optional[dict] = None, hspace: float = 0, wspace: float = 0, show_1d_curves: bool = False, show_joint_dist: bool = False, contour_levels: Optional[collections.abc.Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None, contour_levels_1d: Optional[collections.abc.Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None, contour_levels_2d: Optional[collections.abc.Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None)

1681        self,
1682        options: Optional[dict] = None,
1683        hspace: float = 0,
1684        wspace: float = 0,
1685        show_1d_curves: bool = False,
1686        show_joint_dist: bool = False,
1687        contour_levels: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,

1689        contour_levels_2d: Optional[Sequence[tuple[float, float]]] = None,
1690    ):
1691        """
1692        Constructor.
1693
1694        Parameters
1695        ----------
1696        options : dict, optional
1697            the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special
1698            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can
1699            be one of the outputs of <a
1700            href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/style_api.html#matplotlib.style.matplotlib.style.available"
1701            target="_blank" rel="noopener
1702            noreferrer">`matplotlib.style.available`</a>, or a path to a file.
1703            If using a file, does not use the default rc parameters).
1704
1705        hspace : float, optional
1706            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1707            as a fraction of the average axis height.
1708
1709        wspace : float, optional
1710            The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1711            as a fraction of the average axis width.
1712
1713        show_1d_curves : bool, optional
1714            whether the 1D marginalized curves should be plotted (default:
1715            False)
1716
1717        show_joint_dist : bool, optional
1718            whether to plot the isocontours of the joint distribution (default:
1719            False)
1720
1721        contour_levels : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1722            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded, along with
1723            the associated opacity (default: None). If not specified, defaults
1724            to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1725
1726        contour_levels_1d : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1727            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded (on the 1D
1728            plots), along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not
1729            specified, defaults to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1730
1731        contour_levels_2d : array_like of 2-tuples, optional
1732            the points at which the sigma level should be shaded (on the 2D
1733            plots), along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not
1734            specified, defaults to `[(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)]`.
1735
1736        Notes
1737        -----
1738        For the style sheet reference, please consult <a
1739        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html"
1740        target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">the matplotlib
1741        documentation</a>.
1742
1743        **Regarding `show_joint_dist`**: this argument specifies whether we
1744        wish to plot the p-value of the *joint* distribution, or the p-value of
1745        the probability of a single parameter lying within the bounds projected
1746        onto a parameter axis. For more details, see <a
1747        href="https://arxiv.org/abs/0906.0664" target="_blank" rel="noopener
1748        noreferrer">arXiv:0906.0664</a>, section 2.
1749        """
1750        super().__init__(
1751            options=options,
1752            wspace=wspace,
1753            hspace=hspace,
1754            contour_levels=contour_levels,
1755        )
1756        self.show_1d_curves = show_1d_curves
1757        self.show_joint_dist = show_joint_dist
1758        self._ndim = 2
1759
1760        if contour_levels_1d is None:
1761            self.contour_levels_1d = self.contour_levels
1762        else:
1763            self.contour_levels_1d = _parse_contour_levels(contour_levels_1d)
1764
1765        if contour_levels_2d is None:
1766            self.contour_levels_2d = self.contour_levels
1767        else:
1768            self.contour_levels_2d = _parse_contour_levels(contour_levels_2d)

Constructor.

Parameters
  • options (dict, optional): the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can be one of the outputs of matplotlib.style.available, or a path to a file. If using a file, does not use the default rc parameters).
  • hspace (float, optional): The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis height.
  • wspace (float, optional): The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis width.
  • show_1d_curves (bool, optional): whether the 1D marginalized curves should be plotted (default: False)
  • show_joint_dist (bool, optional): whether to plot the isocontours of the joint distribution (default: False)
  • contour_levels (array_like of 2-tuples, optional): the points at which the sigma level should be shaded, along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not specified, defaults to [(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)].
  • contour_levels_1d (array_like of 2-tuples, optional): the points at which the sigma level should be shaded (on the 1D plots), along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not specified, defaults to [(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)].
  • contour_levels_2d (array_like of 2-tuples, optional): the points at which the sigma level should be shaded (on the 2D plots), along with the associated opacity (default: None). If not specified, defaults to [(1, 0.3), (2, 0.1)].
Notes

For the style sheet reference, please consult the matplotlib documentation.

Regarding show_joint_dist: this argument specifies whether we wish to plot the p-value of the joint distribution, or the p-value of the probability of a single parameter lying within the bounds projected onto a parameter axis. For more details, see arXiv:0906.0664, section 2.

1819            False)
1820
1821        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
1822            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
1823            (default: 'upper right')
1824

1843            raise EmptyFigureError
1844

1846            # this will always exist since we can't plot < 2 parameters
1847            ax = self[self.names[0], self.names[1]]
1848            if not overwrite:
1849                if self.show_1d_curves:
1850                    i, j = 0, -1
1851                else:
1852                    i, j = 1, -2
1853

1855                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1856                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1857                )
1858

1860                    ax.get_legend().remove()

1866                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1867                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
1868                    **kwargs,
1869                )
1870
1871            return ax.legend(
1872                *args,
1873                loc=loc,
1874                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1875                **kwargs,
1876            )

def draw(self, name1: str, name2: str, method: str, *args, **kwargs): 
1938    def draw(
1939        self,
1940        name1: str,
1941        name2: str,
1942        method: str,
1943        *args,
1944        **kwargs,
1945    ):
1946        """
1947        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis where the parameters
1948        `name1` and `name2` have already been plotted.
1949
1950        Parameters
1951        ----------
1952        name1 : str
1953            the name (label) of the first parameter where we want to draw
1954
1955        name2 : str
1956            the name (label) of the second parameter where we want to draw
1957
1958        method : str
1959            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as `plot`,
1960            `scatter`, etc.)
1961
1962        *args
1963            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
1964
1965        **kwargs
1966            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
1967
1968        Returns
1969        -------
1970        Artist
1971            the artist that was drawn on the axis
1972
1973        Raises
1974        ------
1975        EmptyFigureError
1976            if `figure` is not set
1977
1978        AttributeError
1979            if `method` is not a valid plotting method
1980        """
1981        if not hasattr(self[name1, name2], method):
1982            raise AttributeError(
1983                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
1984            )
1985
1986        # get the right color
1987        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1988            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1989            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1990
1991        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1992            # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection
1993            # of artists
1994            handles = getattr(self[name1, name2], method)(*args, **kwargs)
1995            if is_iterable(handles):
1996                for handle in handles:
1997                    if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1998                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1999                        self.handles.append(handle)
2000            else:
2001                if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
2002                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
2003                    self.handles.append(handles)
2004
2005        self[name1, name2].autoscale()
2006        self[name1, name2].relim()
2007        self[name1, name2].autoscale_view()
2008
2009        return handles

2060        """
2061        size = len(fisher)
2062
2063        if size < 2:
2064            raise ValueError("Unable to make a 2D plot with < 2 parameters")
2065
2066        if self.names is not None:
2067            # make sure they have the same names; if not, raise an error
2068            if set(self.names) != set(fisher.names):
2069                raise ValueError(
2070                    f"The Fisher object names ({fisher.names}) "
2071                    f"do not match those on the figure ({self.names})"
2072                )
2073
2074            # otherwise, we reshuffle them
2075            fisher = fisher.sort(key=self.names)
2076
2077        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
2078        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
2079        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
2080            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
2081            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
2082
2083        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
2084            # general figure setup
2085            if self.figure:
2086                fig = self.figure
2087                ax = self.axes
2088            else:
2089                fig = plt.figure(
2090                    figsize=(2 * size, 2 * size),
2091                    clear=True,
2092                )
2093                ax = fig.add_gridspec(
2094                    nrows=size,
2095                    ncols=size,
2096                    hspace=self.hspace,
2097                    wspace=self.wspace,
2098                ).subplots(
2099                    sharex="col",
2100                    sharey=False,
2101                )
2102
2103            # set automatic limits
2104            _set_limits_2d(ax=ax, size=size)
2105
2106            # flag for whether the current artist has already been added to the
2107            # legend handle
2108            added = False
2109            # loop over the parameters
2110            for i, j in product(range(len(fisher.names)), repeat=2):
2111                namey, latex_namey, namex, latex_namex = (
2112                    fisher.names[i],
2113                    fisher.latex_names[i],
2114                    fisher.names[j],
2115                    fisher.latex_names[j],
2116                )
2117                # labels for 2D contours (increasing y)
2118                if i > 0 and j == 0:
2119                    ax[i, j].set_ylabel(latex_namey)
2120
2121                # labels for 2D contours (increasing x)
2122                if i == size - 1:
2123                    ax[i, j].set_xlabel(latex_namex)
2124
2125                # removing any unnecessary axes from the gridspec
2126                if i < j and self.figure is None:
2127                    # calling `remove()` is better than `axis("off")` because
2128                    # then we obtain the proper bounding box
2129                    try:
2130                        ax[i, j].remove()
2131                    except KeyError:
2132                        pass
2133
2134                # plotting the 2D contours
2135                elif i > j:
2136                    # plot 1-sigma 2D curves
2137                    # NOTE this is the "68% of the probability of a
2138                    # single parameter lying within the bounds projected
2139                    # onto a parameter axis"
2140                    _, __, handle = plot_curve_2d(
2141                        fisher,
2142                        namex,
2143                        namey,
2144                        ax=ax[i, j],
2145                        scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[0][0]
2146                        if not self.show_joint_dist
2147                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[0][0])),
2148                        fill=False,
2149                        zorder=20,
2150                        **kwargs,
2151                    )
2152
2153                    if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
2154                        self.handles.append(handle)
2155                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
2156                        added = True
2157
2158                    # same thing, but shaded
2159                    plot_curve_2d(
2160                        fisher,
2161                        namex,
2162                        namey,
2163                        ax=ax[i, j],
2164                        scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[0][0]
2165                        if not self.show_joint_dist
2166                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[0][0])),
2167                        fill=True,
2168                        alpha=self.contour_levels_2d[0][1],
2169                        ec=None,
2170                        zorder=20,
2171                        **kwargs,
2172                    )
2173
2174                    for index in range(1, len(self.contour_levels_2d)):
2175                        # the 2-sigma
2176                        plot_curve_2d(
2177                            fisher,
2178                            namex,
2179                            namey,
2180                            ax=ax[i, j],
2181                            scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[index][0]
2182                            if not self.show_joint_dist
2183                            else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[index][0])),
2184                            fill=False,
2185                            zorder=20,
2186                            **kwargs,
2187                        )
2188
2189                        # same thing, but shaded
2190                        plot_curve_2d(
2191                            fisher,
2192                            namex,
2193                            namey,
2194                            ax=ax[i, j],
2195                            scaling_factor=self.contour_levels_2d[index][0]
2196                            if not self.show_joint_dist
2197                            else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(self.contour_levels_2d[index][0])),
2198                            fill=True,
2199                            alpha=self.contour_levels_2d[index][1],
2200                            ec=None,
2201                            zorder=20,
2202                            **kwargs,
2203                        )
2204
2205                if i == j:
2206                    # plotting the 1D Gaussians
2207                    if self.show_1d_curves is True:
2208                        plot_curve_1d(
2209                            fisher,
2210                            namex,
2211                            ax=ax[i, i],
2212                            **kwargs,
2213                        )
2214
2215                        for contour_level in self.contour_levels_1d:
2216                            _add_shading_1d(
2217                                fisher.fiducials[i],
2218                                fisher.constraints(
2219                                    name=namex,
2220                                    marginalized=True,
2221                                )[0],
2222                                level=contour_level[0],
2223                                ax=ax[i, i],
2224                                alpha=contour_level[1],
2225                                **kwargs,
2226                            )
2227
2228                    else:
2229                        if self.figure is None:
2230                            try:
2231                                ax[i, i].remove()
2232                            except KeyError:
2233                                pass
2234
2235            # set automatic limits
2236            _rescale_limits_2d(ax=ax, size=size)
2237
2238            # marking the fiducials
2239            _mark_fiducials(
2240                fisher=fisher,
2241                ax=ax,
2242                size=size,
2243                mark_fiducials=mark_fiducials,
2244            )
2245
2246        self._figure = fig
2247        self._axes = ax
2248        self._names = fisher.names

Plots the 2D contours (and optionally 1D curves) of the Fisher objects.

Parameters
  • fisher (FisherMatrix): the Fisher object which we want to plot
  • mark_fiducials (bool or dict, optional): whether or not the fiducials should be marked on the plots (default: False). If set to True, uses linestyle='--' and color='black' as the default. If a dictionary, accepts the same keyword arguments as matplotlib.axes.Axes.axvline. If an empty dictionary, uses the default style (determined automatically).
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as plot_curve_2d)
Returns
  • None
Examples

Define a Fisher matrix:

>>> m = FisherMatrix([[3, -2], [-2, 5]], names=['a', 'b'], latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'])

Initiate a figure:

>>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)

Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:

>>> fig.plot(m)

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "fisher_figure2d_plot_example.png",
... dpi=150)

2361
2362    Parameters
2363    ----------
2364    fisher : FisherMatrix
2365        the Fisher matrix which we want to plot
2366
2367    name : str
2368        the name of the parameter which we want to plot
2369
2370    ax : matplotlib.axes.Axes, optional
2371        the axis on which we want to plot the contour (default: None). If None,
2372        plots to a new figure.
2373
2374    **kwargs
2375        any keyword arguments passed to <a
2376        href="https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.plot.html"
2377        target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">`matplotlib.pyplot.plot`</a>.
2378
2379    Returns
2380    -------
2381    A 3-tuple `(Figure, Axes, Artist)`
2382        The figure and the axis on which the artist was drawn on, as well as
2383        the artist itself.
2384
2385    Examples
2386    --------
2387    Define a Fisher matrix:
2388    >>> m = FisherMatrix(
2389    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
2390    ... names=['a', 'b'],
2391    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
2392    ... )
2393
2394    Draw the marginalized parameter `a`:
2395    >>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_1d(m, name='a', ls='--', color='red')
2396
2397    Save it to a file:
2398    >>> fig.savefig(
2399    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "plot_curve_1d_example1.png",
2400    ... dpi=100)

2403    """
2404    if ax is None:
2405        _, ax = plt.subplots()
2406
2407    fid = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)]
2408    sigma = fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True)
2409
2410    return _add_plot_1d(fid, sigma, ax=ax, **kwargs)

Plots a 1D curve (usually marginalized Gaussian) from a Fisher object.

Parameters
  • fisher (FisherMatrix): the Fisher matrix which we want to plot
  • name (str): the name of the parameter which we want to plot
  • ax (matplotlib.axes.Axes, optional): the axis on which we want to plot the contour (default: None). If None, plots to a new figure.
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments passed to matplotlib.pyplot.plot.
Returns
  • A 3-tuple (Figure, Axes, Artist): The figure and the axis on which the artist was drawn on, as well as the artist itself.
Examples

Define a Fisher matrix:

>>> m = FisherMatrix(
... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )

Draw the marginalized parameter a:

>>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_1d(m, name='a', ls='--', color='red')

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "plot_curve_1d_example1.png",
... dpi=100)

2455    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
2456    ... names=['a', 'b'],
2457    ... fiducials=[1, -2],
2458    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
2459    ... )
2460
2461    Draw the 1$\sigma$ contour of the parameter combination `a`, `b`:
2462    >>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_2d(m, name1='a', name2='b', ls='--', color='red', fill=False)
2463
2464    Rescale the view a bit:
2465    >>> _ = ax.autoscale()
2466    >>> _ = ax.relim()
2467    >>> _ = ax.autoscale_view()
2468
2469    Save it to a file:
2470    >>> fig.savefig(
2471    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "plot_curve_2d_example1.png",
2472    ... dpi=100)
2473

2477    -----
2478    The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
2479    """
2480    if ax is None:
2481        _, ax = plt.subplots()
2482
2483    fidx = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name1)]
2484    fidy = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name2)]
2485
2486    a, b, angle = _get_ellipse(fisher, name1, name2)
2487
2488    patch = ax.add_patch(
2489        Ellipse(
2490            xy=(fidx, fidy),
2491            width=2 * a * scaling_factor,
2492            height=2 * b * scaling_factor,
2493            angle=angle,
2494            **kwargs,
2495        ),
2496    )
2497
2498    return (ax.get_figure(), ax, patch)

Plots a 2D curve (usually ellipse) from two parameters of a Fisher object.

Parameters
  • fisher (FisherMatrix): the Fisher matrix which we want to plot
  • name1 (str): the name of the first parameter which we want to plot
  • name2 (str): the name of the second parameter which we want to plot
  • ax (matplotlib.axes.Axes, optional): the axis on which we want to plot the contour (default: None). If None, plots to a new figure.
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments passed to matplotlib.patches.Ellipse.
Returns
  • A 3-tuple (Figure, Axes, Artist): The figure and the axis on which the artist was drawn on, as well as the artist itself.
Examples

Define a Fisher matrix:

>>> m = FisherMatrix(
... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... fiducials=[1, -2],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )

Draw the 1$\sigma$ contour of the parameter combination a, b:

>>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_2d(m, name1='a', name2='b', ls='--', color='red', fill=False)

Rescale the view a bit:

>>> _ = ax.autoscale()
>>> _ = ax.relim()
>>> _ = ax.autoscale_view()

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR", "") / "plot_curve_2d_example1.png",
... dpi=100)

Notes

The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
